WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.415 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.415 --> 00:00:03.381 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.381 --> 00:00:05.313 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.313 --> 00:00:10.388 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.388 --> 00:00:10.930 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: OK.

00:00:10.930 --> 00:00:12.770 align:middle line:90%
Let us start.

00:00:12.770 --> 00:00:17.350 align:middle line:84%
So last time, we started talking
about discrete symmetries.

00:00:17.350 --> 00:00:28.880 align:middle line:90%


00:00:28.880 --> 00:00:30.655 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a
complex scalar theory--

00:00:30.655 --> 00:00:51.550 align:middle line:90%


00:00:51.550 --> 00:00:53.760 align:middle line:84%
so if you have a
complex scalar theory

00:00:53.760 --> 00:00:57.960 align:middle line:84%
and then, in addition
to U1 symmetry,

00:00:57.960 --> 00:01:00.960 align:middle line:84%
classically there are also
discrete symmetries-- firstly

00:01:00.960 --> 00:01:03.750 align:middle line:90%
is parity.

00:01:03.750 --> 00:01:07.682 align:middle line:84%
So we normally denote with
a symbol P and the act

00:01:07.682 --> 00:01:12.945 align:middle line:90%
on x mu by t taken to minus x.

00:01:12.945 --> 00:01:14.172 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:01:14.172 --> 00:01:17.010 align:middle line:84%
So you just flip all
the spatial direction.

00:01:17.010 --> 00:01:18.540 align:middle line:90%
And you also have time reversal.

00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:23.350 align:middle line:90%


00:01:23.350 --> 00:01:23.890 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:01:23.890 --> 00:01:24.880 align:middle line:90%
Time reversal.

00:01:24.880 --> 00:01:30.100 align:middle line:84%
And then I normally write
as a script T on x mu,

00:01:30.100 --> 00:01:32.990 align:middle line:90%
then take to the minus t and x.

00:01:32.990 --> 00:01:33.490 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:01:33.490 --> 00:01:35.260 align:middle line:90%
It does not do anything with x.

00:01:35.260 --> 00:01:43.760 align:middle line:84%
And then we also have a
charge conjugation, which

00:01:43.760 --> 00:01:47.510 align:middle line:90%
takes phi and goes to phi star.

00:01:47.510 --> 00:01:49.640 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:01:49.640 --> 00:01:54.650 align:middle line:84%
And so of course, our goal is
to understand the symmetries

00:01:54.650 --> 00:01:56.660 align:middle line:90%
at the quantum level.

00:01:56.660 --> 00:01:57.230 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:01:57.230 --> 00:01:59.840 align:middle line:84%
So at the quantum level--
so you're already--

00:01:59.840 --> 00:02:11.030 align:middle line:84%
then in quantum mechanics,
symmetries are--

00:02:11.030 --> 00:02:16.980 align:middle line:90%
symmetry transformations.

00:02:16.980 --> 00:02:23.265 align:middle line:84%
So they are corresponding to
unitary, OK, transformations.

00:02:23.265 --> 00:02:23.765 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:02:23.765 --> 00:02:26.760 align:middle line:90%


00:02:26.760 --> 00:02:27.260 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:02:27.260 --> 00:02:29.135 align:middle line:84%
They corresponding to
unitary transformation.

00:02:29.135 --> 00:02:32.210 align:middle line:84%
We already have done that
for continuous symmetries.

00:02:32.210 --> 00:02:35.270 align:middle line:84%
And the same thing is with
the discrete symmetries.

00:02:35.270 --> 00:02:38.300 align:middle line:84%
And in quantum mechanics,
the implementation

00:02:38.300 --> 00:02:40.460 align:middle line:84%
of the discrete
symmetries are also

00:02:40.460 --> 00:02:42.140 align:middle line:90%
through some unitary operator.

00:02:42.140 --> 00:02:45.260 align:middle line:90%


00:02:45.260 --> 00:02:53.780 align:middle line:84%
And so there's a slight
subtly with the time reversal

00:02:53.780 --> 00:02:57.860 align:middle line:84%
because all the other symmetry
transformations corresponding

00:02:57.860 --> 00:03:02.735 align:middle line:84%
to the unitary transformations,
except for the time reversal.

00:03:02.735 --> 00:03:06.350 align:middle line:84%
That actually is corresponding
to the anti-unitary

00:03:06.350 --> 00:03:07.500 align:middle line:90%
transformations.

00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:11.860 align:middle line:84%
So have you seen that
in quantum mechanics?

00:03:11.860 --> 00:03:12.360 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:12.860 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:12.860 --> 00:03:14.670 align:middle line:90%
Let me just review it here.

00:03:14.670 --> 00:03:16.980 align:middle line:90%
So yeah.

00:03:16.980 --> 00:03:19.230 align:middle line:84%
So previously, I
want to say "recall."

00:03:19.230 --> 00:03:21.930 align:middle line:90%
But we don't have to recall it.

00:03:21.930 --> 00:03:28.210 align:middle line:84%
So say-- so let's denote the
UT as the unitary operator.

00:03:28.210 --> 00:03:33.645 align:middle line:84%
So this is the unitary
operator for time reversal.

00:03:33.645 --> 00:03:37.470 align:middle line:90%


00:03:37.470 --> 00:03:39.030 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:03:39.030 --> 00:03:44.360 align:middle line:84%
And then the claim is
that this has to be--

00:03:44.360 --> 00:03:48.520 align:middle line:90%
this should be anti-linear.

00:03:48.520 --> 00:03:52.760 align:middle line:90%


00:03:52.760 --> 00:03:55.100 align:middle line:84%
And it's not actually
ordinary unitary.

00:03:55.100 --> 00:03:56.540 align:middle line:90%
It's called the anti-unitary.

00:03:56.540 --> 00:04:00.860 align:middle line:90%


00:04:00.860 --> 00:04:03.460 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:04:03.460 --> 00:04:08.710 align:middle line:84%
And so now let's try to explain
where those things come from.

00:04:08.710 --> 00:04:11.160 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that you
have a system which we

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:16.430 align:middle line:90%
say is time reversal invariant.

00:04:16.430 --> 00:04:20.769 align:middle line:84%
So by definition,
the symmetry is

00:04:20.769 --> 00:04:26.770 align:middle line:84%
that the corresponding
transformation of the symmetry

00:04:26.770 --> 00:04:28.520 align:middle line:84%
should commute with
your Hamiltonian.

00:04:28.520 --> 00:04:29.020 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:04:29.020 --> 00:04:31.130 align:middle line:84%
So this is what we
mean by the system

00:04:31.130 --> 00:04:33.560 align:middle line:90%
to be time reversal invariant.

00:04:33.560 --> 00:04:34.060 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:04:34.060 --> 00:04:39.340 align:middle line:90%


00:04:39.340 --> 00:04:42.100 align:middle line:84%
So here, I'm just talking about
it just in quantum mechanics.

00:04:42.100 --> 00:04:42.600 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:04:42.600 --> 00:04:47.450 align:middle line:84%
Let's not even worry
about the field theory.

00:04:47.450 --> 00:04:50.720 align:middle line:84%
So now-- so suppose we
have a time reversal

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:55.550 align:middle line:84%
invariant system, which
the time reversal operator

00:04:55.550 --> 00:04:58.380 align:middle line:90%
commutes with your Hamiltonian.

00:04:58.380 --> 00:05:04.540 align:middle line:84%
And then let's act this
UT on the wave function.

00:05:04.540 --> 00:05:05.040 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:05:05.040 --> 00:05:09.280 align:middle line:90%
Then you get some psi prime.

00:05:09.280 --> 00:05:19.470 align:middle line:84%
So by time reversal, we
expect physically, OK,

00:05:19.470 --> 00:05:25.640 align:middle line:84%
if psi satisfy the standard
Schrodinger equation,

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:35.540 align:middle line:84%
and then psi prime should
satisfy the Schrodinger

00:05:35.540 --> 00:05:37.430 align:middle line:90%
equation with t goes to minus t.

00:05:37.430 --> 00:05:39.690 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:05:39.690 --> 00:05:49.410 align:middle line:84%
It's the same
Schrodinger equation,

00:05:49.410 --> 00:05:51.370 align:middle line:90%
but with t goes to minus t.

00:05:51.370 --> 00:05:51.870 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:05:51.870 --> 00:05:53.537 align:middle line:84%
So that's what we
mean by time reversal.

00:05:53.537 --> 00:05:55.590 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:05:55.590 --> 00:05:57.670 align:middle line:90%
So now let's try to do that.

00:05:57.670 --> 00:06:00.360 align:middle line:84%
So let's start
with this equation.

00:06:00.360 --> 00:06:08.950 align:middle line:84%
And now let's just act by UH
from the left on this equation.

00:06:08.950 --> 00:06:09.490 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:06:09.490 --> 00:06:14.090 align:middle line:90%
So the left-hand side has UH.

00:06:14.090 --> 00:06:14.590 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:06:14.590 --> 00:06:15.910 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, it means
that-- yeah, yeah.

00:06:15.910 --> 00:06:17.827 align:middle line:84%
Before too [? I leave it ?]
do one more step--

00:06:17.827 --> 00:06:20.390 align:middle line:90%


00:06:20.390 --> 00:06:24.598 align:middle line:84%
which means that
the psi prime should

00:06:24.598 --> 00:06:25.890 align:middle line:90%
satisfy the following equation.

00:06:25.890 --> 00:06:31.470 align:middle line:90%


00:06:31.470 --> 00:06:32.250 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:06:32.250 --> 00:06:33.998 align:middle line:84%
So you just take t
equal to minus t.

00:06:33.998 --> 00:06:35.790 align:middle line:84%
And then you get the
additional minus sign.

00:06:35.790 --> 00:06:36.300 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:06:36.300 --> 00:06:42.640 align:middle line:84%
So psi prime should
satisfy this equation.

00:06:42.640 --> 00:06:48.210 align:middle line:84%
So now let's see how you
get this equation from here

00:06:48.210 --> 00:06:52.870 align:middle line:84%
by using this relation,
OK, by using this relation.

00:06:52.870 --> 00:06:53.920 align:middle line:90%
So this is simple.

00:06:53.920 --> 00:06:59.760 align:middle line:84%
Let's just add a U on the
left of this equation.

00:06:59.760 --> 00:07:05.840 align:middle line:84%
So let me call this equation
star and this one star-star.

00:07:05.840 --> 00:07:21.870 align:middle line:84%
So if I add UT on star, then on
the right-hand side, UT commute

00:07:21.870 --> 00:07:24.495 align:middle line:90%
with H. OK?

00:07:24.495 --> 00:07:31.830 align:middle line:84%
So on the right-hand side, we
just directly get UT H psi.

00:07:31.830 --> 00:07:34.240 align:middle line:90%
And we can just commute them.

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:37.530 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
same as H psi UT--

00:07:37.530 --> 00:07:41.340 align:middle line:90%


00:07:41.340 --> 00:07:43.350 align:middle line:84%
UT psi and this is
just psi, psi prime.

00:07:43.350 --> 00:07:45.480 align:middle line:84%
So the right-hand side
just gets psi prime.

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:48.030 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:07:48.030 --> 00:07:54.690 align:middle line:84%
And then from the side,
you get UT i partial t psi.

00:07:54.690 --> 00:07:58.430 align:middle line:90%


00:07:58.430 --> 00:08:00.930 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:08:00.930 --> 00:08:04.780 align:middle line:84%
So in the ordinary situation,
we would have trouble.

00:08:04.780 --> 00:08:10.200 align:middle line:84%
So if you-- because this is
the operator. i is a c-number.

00:08:10.200 --> 00:08:12.370 align:middle line:84%
And the partial
t is some number.

00:08:12.370 --> 00:08:15.450 align:middle line:84%
So you can just directly
pass through this i

00:08:15.450 --> 00:08:16.470 align:middle line:90%
and the partial t.

00:08:16.470 --> 00:08:21.620 align:middle line:84%
But when UT act on psi, then
you get the same equation

00:08:21.620 --> 00:08:24.540 align:middle line:84%
rather than the equation
with a minus sign.

00:08:24.540 --> 00:08:25.040 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:08:25.040 --> 00:08:26.710 align:middle line:90%
Then you have trouble.

00:08:26.710 --> 00:08:31.765 align:middle line:84%
And the only way to get that
equation is to require--

00:08:31.765 --> 00:08:38.820 align:middle line:90%


00:08:38.820 --> 00:08:47.270 align:middle line:84%
we require-- when UT pass
through i, take it to minus i.

00:08:47.270 --> 00:08:52.900 align:middle line:90%


00:08:52.900 --> 00:08:53.400 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:08:53.400 --> 00:08:56.620 align:middle line:90%
We impose this condition.

00:08:56.620 --> 00:08:59.360 align:middle line:84%
When UT pass through
i, you get a minus i.

00:08:59.360 --> 00:08:59.860 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:08:59.860 --> 00:09:07.390 align:middle line:90%


00:09:07.390 --> 00:09:16.890 align:middle line:84%
So this means-- so we can
define anti-linear operator.

00:09:16.890 --> 00:09:21.930 align:middle line:84%
Anti-linear operator is
defined to be the following.

00:09:21.930 --> 00:09:26.800 align:middle line:84%
It means that if you have some
operator a act on some number

00:09:26.800 --> 00:09:32.620 align:middle line:84%
c, when you pass through that
number c, you get c star a.

00:09:32.620 --> 00:09:33.390 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:09:33.390 --> 00:09:37.950 align:middle line:84%
So anti-linear operator a is
defined to have this property.

00:09:37.950 --> 00:09:40.960 align:middle line:84%
And c is just an
ordinary c number,

00:09:40.960 --> 00:09:42.540 align:middle line:90%
OK, an ordinary c number.

00:09:42.540 --> 00:09:45.420 align:middle line:90%
So you see here UT.

00:09:45.420 --> 00:09:49.560 align:middle line:84%
Is order for UT to be ready to
be a time reversal operator.

00:09:49.560 --> 00:09:53.190 align:middle line:84%
And UT had to be
anti-linear, OK, so that,

00:09:53.190 --> 00:09:56.370 align:middle line:84%
when you pass through i, it
takes i equal to minus i.

00:09:56.370 --> 00:09:59.220 align:middle line:84%
Because the minus i is the
complex conjugate of i.

00:09:59.220 --> 00:09:59.750 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:09:59.750 --> 00:10:00.250 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:10:00.250 --> 00:10:01.260 align:middle line:90%
Any questions on this?

00:10:01.260 --> 00:10:04.755 align:middle line:90%


00:10:04.755 --> 00:10:05.255 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:10:05.255 --> 00:10:09.350 align:middle line:90%


00:10:09.350 --> 00:10:10.850 align:middle line:90%
So yeah.

00:10:10.850 --> 00:10:16.941 align:middle line:90%
So UT should be anti-linear.

00:10:16.941 --> 00:10:21.090 align:middle line:90%


00:10:21.090 --> 00:10:22.680 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:22.680 --> 00:10:26.110 align:middle line:84%
So also, for
anti-linear operator,

00:10:26.110 --> 00:10:28.470 align:middle line:84%
the adjoints should be
defined differently.

00:10:28.470 --> 00:10:29.160 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:10:29.160 --> 00:10:31.710 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
you started off

00:10:31.710 --> 00:10:35.070 align:middle line:84%
with trying to show
star-star using

00:10:35.070 --> 00:10:37.380 align:middle line:90%
this-- how UT acts on star.

00:10:37.380 --> 00:10:41.545 align:middle line:84%
But then you kind of inserted
this requirement ad hoc

00:10:41.545 --> 00:10:42.420 align:middle line:90%
to satisfy star star.

00:10:42.420 --> 00:10:43.020 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: That's right.

00:10:43.020 --> 00:10:43.812 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, that's right.

00:10:43.812 --> 00:10:45.600 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: So I'm a bit confused.

00:10:45.600 --> 00:10:49.700 align:middle line:84%
Then how do you come up-- why
the star-star [INAUDIBLE]??

00:10:49.700 --> 00:10:51.640 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: No, the
star-star is the definition

00:10:51.640 --> 00:10:52.450 align:middle line:90%
of time reversal.

00:10:52.450 --> 00:10:55.090 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:10:55.090 --> 00:10:58.510 align:middle line:84%
Star-star is what physically
we mean by time reversal.

00:10:58.510 --> 00:11:01.120 align:middle line:84%
If you want something to
implement the time reversal,

00:11:01.120 --> 00:11:03.530 align:middle line:90%
it has to achieve star-star.

00:11:03.530 --> 00:11:04.030 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:11:04.030 --> 00:11:07.080 align:middle line:90%


00:11:07.080 --> 00:11:09.720 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:11:09.720 --> 00:11:10.220 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:10.220 --> 00:11:10.720 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:11:10.720 --> 00:11:13.990 align:middle line:84%
And then we derived
that in order

00:11:13.990 --> 00:11:19.030 align:middle line:84%
to achieve the time reversal,
then UT has to be anti-linear.

00:11:19.030 --> 00:11:22.390 align:middle line:84%
And then because
ant-linear operator

00:11:22.390 --> 00:11:26.020 align:middle line:84%
has this weird
property, the adjoint

00:11:26.020 --> 00:11:28.150 align:middle line:84%
of anti-linear
operator-- the definition

00:11:28.150 --> 00:11:29.450 align:middle line:90%
should also be changed.

00:11:29.450 --> 00:11:29.950 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:11:29.950 --> 00:11:45.620 align:middle line:84%
So the adjoint of
anti-linear operator A

00:11:45.620 --> 00:11:52.590 align:middle line:84%
is defined to be, say, if
you have psi, A dagger chi.

00:11:52.590 --> 00:11:53.580 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:11:53.580 --> 00:11:58.140 align:middle line:84%
If A is an ordinary
operator, and then

00:11:58.140 --> 00:12:00.060 align:middle line:84%
the definition of the
adjoint is that this

00:12:00.060 --> 00:12:02.320 align:middle line:90%
is equal to A psi chi.

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:02.820 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:12:02.820 --> 00:12:04.900 align:middle line:84%
So this is a
standard definition.

00:12:04.900 --> 00:12:05.531 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:12:05.531 --> 00:12:06.156 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:12:06.156 --> 00:12:08.343 align:middle line:84%
So I was just
confused about how you

00:12:08.343 --> 00:12:13.390 align:middle line:84%
deal with making multiplication,
scalar multiplication

00:12:13.390 --> 00:12:18.462 align:middle line:84%
noncommutative and I was
wondering why you couldn't do--

00:12:18.462 --> 00:12:23.090 align:middle line:84%
wouldn't it make sense to just
say that UT and H anti commute?

00:12:23.090 --> 00:12:27.260 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: UT and H anti-commute?

00:12:27.260 --> 00:12:30.700 align:middle line:90%


00:12:30.700 --> 00:12:33.370 align:middle line:90%
So by taking the--

00:12:33.370 --> 00:12:36.300 align:middle line:90%
yeah, you can also do that.

00:12:36.300 --> 00:12:38.050 align:middle line:90%
It just does not work as well.

00:12:38.050 --> 00:12:38.980 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:12:38.980 --> 00:12:40.300 align:middle line:90%
You see whatever it works.

00:12:40.300 --> 00:12:41.440 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, yeah.

00:12:41.440 --> 00:12:45.160 align:middle line:84%
It's much easier just to make
the UT to be anti-linear.

00:12:45.160 --> 00:12:45.790 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:12:45.790 --> 00:12:46.390 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:12:46.390 --> 00:12:47.200 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, yeah.

00:12:47.200 --> 00:12:49.390 align:middle line:84%
For this particular
equation, it can work.

00:12:49.390 --> 00:12:52.120 align:middle line:84%
But then you have to be against
the principle that somehow

00:12:52.120 --> 00:12:54.250 align:middle line:90%
H commute with the symmetry.

00:12:54.250 --> 00:12:55.030 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, yeah.

00:12:55.030 --> 00:12:57.598 align:middle line:84%
That is considered to be
more sacred a principle.

00:12:57.598 --> 00:12:58.098 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:12:58.098 --> 00:13:01.770 align:middle line:90%


00:13:01.770 --> 00:13:03.660 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:13:03.660 --> 00:13:07.940 align:middle line:90%
And indeed-- yeah, yeah.

00:13:07.940 --> 00:13:10.540 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:13:10.540 --> 00:13:11.040 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:11.040 --> 00:13:12.110 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:13:12.110 --> 00:13:14.640 align:middle line:84%
So the way we define the adjoint
should also be different.

00:13:14.640 --> 00:13:16.620 align:middle line:90%
So this is standard definition.

00:13:16.620 --> 00:13:20.860 align:middle line:84%
So for anti-linear, you
have this definition.

00:13:20.860 --> 00:13:23.080 align:middle line:84%
And then you put
the additional star.

00:13:23.080 --> 00:13:24.890 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:13:24.890 --> 00:13:26.380 align:middle line:90%
You put an additional star.

00:13:26.380 --> 00:13:28.130 align:middle line:84%
And the reason you put
the additional star

00:13:28.130 --> 00:13:32.420 align:middle line:84%
is precisely due
to this property.

00:13:32.420 --> 00:13:33.620 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:13:33.620 --> 00:13:38.330 align:middle line:84%
Because remember, if you
put a complex conjugate,

00:13:38.330 --> 00:13:40.022 align:middle line:84%
put the c number
here, and then you

00:13:40.022 --> 00:13:41.480 align:middle line:84%
should be able to
take the c number

00:13:41.480 --> 00:13:45.320 align:middle line:90%
outside this kind of overlap.

00:13:45.320 --> 00:13:47.570 align:middle line:84%
But in order to be
compatible with the property

00:13:47.570 --> 00:13:50.090 align:middle line:84%
of the anti-linear
operator, then you

00:13:50.090 --> 00:13:54.560 align:middle line:84%
have to define the adjoint
to be this way so that you

00:13:54.560 --> 00:13:55.700 align:middle line:90%
have a consistent story.

00:13:55.700 --> 00:13:57.580 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:13:57.580 --> 00:14:00.730 align:middle line:84%
Just I will leave it to
you yourself as an exercise

00:14:00.730 --> 00:14:03.520 align:middle line:84%
to show this is actually
the right definition.

00:14:03.520 --> 00:14:04.540 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:14:04.540 --> 00:14:13.510 align:middle line:84%
And then we can define
the anti-unitary

00:14:13.510 --> 00:14:16.510 align:middle line:84%
as that, if you have an
operator with anti-unitary,

00:14:16.510 --> 00:14:24.910 align:middle line:90%
it means U phi, U chi.

00:14:24.910 --> 00:14:27.430 align:middle line:84%
So standard unitary
condition is just

00:14:27.430 --> 00:14:30.640 align:middle line:84%
that this is equal to chi--
and the psi and the chi.

00:14:30.640 --> 00:14:32.000 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:36.910 align:middle line:84%
And now for the anti-unitary,
again, you just put the star.

00:14:36.910 --> 00:14:37.410 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:14:37.410 --> 00:14:38.327 align:middle line:90%
You just put the star.

00:14:38.327 --> 00:14:43.780 align:middle line:90%


00:14:43.780 --> 00:14:44.280 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:14:44.280 --> 00:14:51.030 align:middle line:84%
So the claim is that the UT,
the time reversal operator,

00:14:51.030 --> 00:14:55.920 align:middle line:84%
should be an anti-unitary
operator, uh, in order

00:14:55.920 --> 00:14:59.080 align:middle line:84%
to be a symmetry, in
order to be a symmetry.

00:14:59.080 --> 00:14:59.580 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:14:59.580 --> 00:15:05.520 align:middle line:84%
So this is just a brief
review of time reversal

00:15:05.520 --> 00:15:06.750 align:middle line:90%
in quantum mechanics.

00:15:06.750 --> 00:15:12.760 align:middle line:84%
So now let's look at the quantum
version of those symmetries

00:15:12.760 --> 00:15:13.760 align:middle line:90%
in quantum field theory.

00:15:13.760 --> 00:15:14.260 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:15:14.260 --> 00:15:17.870 align:middle line:90%
So first, let's do the warm-up.

00:15:17.870 --> 00:15:22.220 align:middle line:84%
Before let's do it
for the Dirac theory,

00:15:22.220 --> 00:15:31.080 align:middle line:84%
let's warm up for complex scalar
fields, which is much simpler.

00:15:31.080 --> 00:15:31.580 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:15:31.580 --> 00:15:34.140 align:middle line:90%


00:15:34.140 --> 00:15:38.490 align:middle line:84%
So in this theory, the
action is invariant, we said,

00:15:38.490 --> 00:15:39.490 align:middle line:90%
under those symmetries.

00:15:39.490 --> 00:15:39.990 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:15:39.990 --> 00:15:43.880 align:middle line:84%
If we just flip the
spatial direction,

00:15:43.880 --> 00:15:47.218 align:middle line:84%
clearly that Lagrangian
is invariant.

00:15:47.218 --> 00:15:49.760 align:middle line:84%
If we leave the time direction
because the time derivative is

00:15:49.760 --> 00:15:51.260 align:middle line:90%
quadratic, it's also invariant.

00:15:51.260 --> 00:15:55.520 align:middle line:84%
And again, if you
change phi to phi star,

00:15:55.520 --> 00:15:56.810 align:middle line:90%
the Lagrangian is invariant.

00:15:56.810 --> 00:15:58.250 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:58.250 --> 00:16:01.910 align:middle line:84%
So quantum mechanically,
those symmetries

00:16:01.910 --> 00:16:10.190 align:middle line:84%
should be implemented by
some unitary operator.

00:16:10.190 --> 00:16:10.760 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:10.760 --> 00:16:17.630 align:middle line:84%
So now the parity
transformation on the field

00:16:17.630 --> 00:16:20.840 align:middle line:84%
to the corresponding to
you start with phi x.

00:16:20.840 --> 00:16:25.060 align:middle line:90%
And then you go to phi prime x.

00:16:25.060 --> 00:16:30.720 align:middle line:84%
So phi prime x should
be equal to phi px.

00:16:30.720 --> 00:16:31.320 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:33.900 align:middle line:90%
This means that the--

00:16:33.900 --> 00:16:38.030 align:middle line:84%
and then just put-- yeah, you
can also put the phase here.

00:16:38.030 --> 00:16:39.170 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:16:39.170 --> 00:16:41.450 align:middle line:84%
So you can show that this
transformation certainly is

00:16:41.450 --> 00:16:43.520 align:middle line:90%
a symmetry of this Lagrangian.

00:16:43.520 --> 00:16:44.900 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:16:44.900 --> 00:16:47.600 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, because as I said,
if you just flip it,

00:16:47.600 --> 00:16:49.127 align:middle line:90%
it does not change anything.

00:16:49.127 --> 00:16:50.960 align:middle line:84%
But you can also put
an arbitrary phase here

00:16:50.960 --> 00:16:52.080 align:middle line:90%
in principle.

00:16:52.080 --> 00:16:52.580 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:16:52.580 --> 00:16:54.622 align:middle line:84%
You can in principle put
an arbitrary phase here.

00:16:54.622 --> 00:16:58.850 align:middle line:84%
Because they all only depend
on the phi and phi dagger.

00:16:58.850 --> 00:16:59.870 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:16:59.870 --> 00:17:05.359 align:middle line:90%
And so this is p.

00:17:05.359 --> 00:17:07.880 align:middle line:90%
And then this is the t.

00:17:07.880 --> 00:17:10.400 align:middle line:84%
Then corresponding
to phi x, then it

00:17:10.400 --> 00:17:17.220 align:middle line:84%
goes to some phi prime x
equal to, again, some phase--

00:17:17.220 --> 00:17:20.220 align:middle line:90%
so phi tx.

00:17:20.220 --> 00:17:22.970 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:17:22.970 --> 00:17:31.260 align:middle line:84%
And then the charge conjugation
normally is called C.

00:17:31.260 --> 00:17:33.930 align:middle line:84%
So parity is normally
called the P. OK?

00:17:33.930 --> 00:17:37.215 align:middle line:84%
So here, it's
corresponding to phi

00:17:37.215 --> 00:17:47.880 align:middle line:84%
x, goes to phi prime x
equal to eta P phi star x.

00:17:47.880 --> 00:17:48.380 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:17:48.380 --> 00:17:53.230 align:middle line:90%


00:17:53.230 --> 00:17:56.630 align:middle line:84%
So in each case, such
kind of transformation

00:17:56.630 --> 00:17:59.013 align:middle line:84%
should be generated by
some unitary operator.

00:17:59.013 --> 00:18:00.680 align:middle line:84%
So for example, this
should be generated

00:18:00.680 --> 00:18:05.165 align:middle line:90%
by UP phi x UP dagger.

00:18:05.165 --> 00:18:07.770 align:middle line:90%


00:18:07.770 --> 00:18:08.310 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:18:08.310 --> 00:18:11.670 align:middle line:84%
And then similarity for
this one, we call the UT--

00:18:11.670 --> 00:18:12.540 align:middle line:90%
UT dagger.

00:18:12.540 --> 00:18:15.300 align:middle line:84%
And here, you see it
in UC dagger similarly.

00:18:15.300 --> 00:18:16.710 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:18:16.710 --> 00:18:18.210 align:middle line:84%
So at the quantum
level, this should

00:18:18.210 --> 00:18:21.300 align:middle line:84%
be generated by some action
of some unitary operator.

00:18:21.300 --> 00:18:22.020 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:18:22.020 --> 00:18:24.520 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Do you always have
this U1 symmetry or do you have

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:27.550 align:middle line:84%
-- is there an interacting
theory where you have one power

00:18:27.550 --> 00:18:28.430 align:middle line:90%
of phi.

00:18:28.430 --> 00:18:29.273 align:middle line:90%
But we don't have--

00:18:29.273 --> 00:18:29.940 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Sorry?

00:18:29.940 --> 00:18:32.010 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So you can
add an arbitrary phase?

00:18:32.010 --> 00:18:33.930 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: No, no.

00:18:33.930 --> 00:18:35.550 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to talk
about the phase.

00:18:35.550 --> 00:18:35.730 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:18:35.730 --> 00:18:37.230 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to talk
about the phase.

00:18:37.230 --> 00:18:42.270 align:middle line:84%
So if you are even looking
at that Lagrangian,

00:18:42.270 --> 00:18:45.060 align:middle line:84%
and then you see you put the
phase, this is invariant.

00:18:45.060 --> 00:18:46.530 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:46.530 --> 00:18:52.590 align:middle line:84%
But now the question is, can
those phases be arbitrary?

00:18:52.590 --> 00:18:53.090 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:18:53.090 --> 00:18:55.520 align:middle line:84%
The question is then, can
those phases be arbitrary?

00:18:55.520 --> 00:19:02.160 align:middle line:90%


00:19:02.160 --> 00:19:05.880 align:middle line:84%
So in the case of this
complex scalar, actually

00:19:05.880 --> 00:19:07.440 align:middle line:90%
it should not be.

00:19:07.440 --> 00:19:10.870 align:middle line:84%
So let's use the
example of the parity.

00:19:10.870 --> 00:19:16.040 align:middle line:84%
So we know that when you
do parity twice, OK--

00:19:16.040 --> 00:19:18.920 align:middle line:84%
if you do parity twice,
you should go back

00:19:18.920 --> 00:19:20.270 align:middle line:90%
to your original.

00:19:20.270 --> 00:19:21.770 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, your system
does not change.

00:19:21.770 --> 00:19:22.270 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:19:22.270 --> 00:19:25.200 align:middle line:84%
If you just do reflections while
your system does not change.

00:19:25.200 --> 00:19:30.960 align:middle line:84%
So that means that, when you
do this twice, you should--

00:19:30.960 --> 00:19:32.640 align:middle line:84%
you haven't changed
anything at all.

00:19:32.640 --> 00:19:33.330 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:19:33.330 --> 00:19:37.202 align:middle line:84%
So when we do it twice, the
phi should come back to itself.

00:19:37.202 --> 00:19:39.800 align:middle line:84%
And indeed, this P-squared,
if you do it twice,

00:19:39.800 --> 00:19:40.980 align:middle line:90%
comes back to itself.

00:19:40.980 --> 00:19:43.450 align:middle line:84%
But then this phase should
also come back to itself.

00:19:43.450 --> 00:19:43.950 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:19:43.950 --> 00:19:47.480 align:middle line:90%
So that means that the--

00:19:47.480 --> 00:19:51.480 align:middle line:84%
eta P-squared should
be equal to 1.

00:19:51.480 --> 00:19:51.980 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:19:51.980 --> 00:19:54.980 align:middle line:90%


00:19:54.980 --> 00:19:58.310 align:middle line:84%
So if you wanted the symmetry
to come back to itself

00:19:58.310 --> 00:20:03.460 align:middle line:84%
and then eta a P, then it
can only be plus-minus 1.

00:20:03.460 --> 00:20:04.970 align:middle line:90%
But it actually can be minus 1.

00:20:04.970 --> 00:20:05.470 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:20:05.470 --> 00:20:06.720 align:middle line:90%
It does not have to be plus 1.

00:20:06.720 --> 00:20:13.930 align:middle line:84%
So recall when eta P is equal
to plus 1, we call it a scalar.

00:20:13.930 --> 00:20:18.807 align:middle line:84%
When eta P is a minus 1,
we call it a pseudoscalar.

00:20:18.807 --> 00:20:24.280 align:middle line:90%


00:20:24.280 --> 00:20:26.050 align:middle line:90%
We call it pseudoscalar.

00:20:26.050 --> 00:20:28.020 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:20:28.020 --> 00:20:40.510 align:middle line:84%
And a similar thing can be
said about the eta t and eta c.

00:20:40.510 --> 00:20:41.010 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:20:41.010 --> 00:20:55.510 align:middle line:90%


00:20:55.510 --> 00:21:00.220 align:middle line:84%
So by definition, this
unitary operator acts on phi.

00:21:00.220 --> 00:21:03.720 align:middle line:90%
It should act as this.

00:21:03.720 --> 00:21:05.980 align:middle line:90%
So now we can--

00:21:05.980 --> 00:21:11.340 align:middle line:84%
and now remember
the phi is expressed

00:21:11.340 --> 00:21:18.000 align:middle line:84%
in terms of the creation
and annihilation operators.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:32.800 align:middle line:90%


00:21:32.800 --> 00:21:35.410 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:21:35.410 --> 00:21:41.248 align:middle line:90%
So by requiring-- yes?

00:21:41.248 --> 00:21:43.105 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
scalar or pseudoscalar

00:21:43.105 --> 00:21:45.515 align:middle line:84%
is it true that if
eta P is equal to one

00:21:45.515 --> 00:21:47.602 align:middle line:90%
then eta T and eta C also be 1?

00:21:47.602 --> 00:21:48.310 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: No, no.

00:21:48.310 --> 00:21:49.370 align:middle line:90%
They don't have to be.

00:21:49.370 --> 00:21:51.090 align:middle line:90%
No, no.

00:21:51.090 --> 00:21:52.330 align:middle line:90%
They don't have to be.

00:21:52.330 --> 00:21:54.930 align:middle line:84%
They can be-- say
this equal to 1.

00:21:54.930 --> 00:21:56.830 align:middle line:90%
eta T can be minus 1.

00:21:56.830 --> 00:21:57.370 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, yeah.

00:21:57.370 --> 00:21:58.180 align:middle line:90%
They don't have to be.

00:21:58.180 --> 00:21:58.680 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:21:58.680 --> 00:22:02.284 align:middle line:90%


00:22:02.284 --> 00:22:03.200 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:22:03.200 --> 00:22:03.783 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yes?

00:22:03.783 --> 00:22:07.057 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: If eta is one, its a
scalar in what sense, I guess?

00:22:07.057 --> 00:22:07.640 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Huh?

00:22:07.640 --> 00:22:09.175 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: It's
scalar in what sense?

00:22:09.175 --> 00:22:13.290 align:middle line:84%
Especially for the other eta's
don't have a [INAUDIBLE] Like,

00:22:13.290 --> 00:22:17.052 align:middle line:84%
I don't understand what is
a scalar it is equal to 1.

00:22:17.052 --> 00:22:18.760 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: You just
say it's a convention.

00:22:18.760 --> 00:22:20.820 align:middle line:90%
It's a name.

00:22:20.820 --> 00:22:23.260 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, we just want to
distinguish these two cases.

00:22:23.260 --> 00:22:25.560 align:middle line:84%
So this is-- so when
you say it's a scalar,

00:22:25.560 --> 00:22:27.390 align:middle line:84%
we should say this is
the ordinary scalar.

00:22:27.390 --> 00:22:29.100 align:middle line:90%
s this is called a pseudoscalar.

00:22:29.100 --> 00:22:29.640 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:22:29.640 --> 00:22:32.860 align:middle line:84%
We just want to distinguish
these two cases.

00:22:32.860 --> 00:22:33.360 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:22:33.360 --> 00:22:36.523 align:middle line:90%


00:22:36.523 --> 00:22:37.190 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:22:37.190 --> 00:22:37.760 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:22:37.760 --> 00:22:42.435 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: So if [INAUDIBLE]

00:22:42.435 --> 00:22:43.060 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

00:22:43.060 --> 00:22:45.475 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:22:45.475 --> 00:22:46.100 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

00:22:46.100 --> 00:22:50.660 align:middle line:90%
So it's getting complicated.

00:22:50.660 --> 00:22:54.980 align:middle line:84%
You can you can try to invent
eight names for these, where

00:22:54.980 --> 00:22:57.080 align:middle line:90%
there are eight possibilities.

00:22:57.080 --> 00:23:01.450 align:middle line:84%
And people normally don't bother
to invent eight names for it.

00:23:01.450 --> 00:23:05.630 align:middle line:84%
And since the parity
is often used,

00:23:05.630 --> 00:23:09.620 align:middle line:84%
and so they just talk
about the parity.

00:23:09.620 --> 00:23:10.520 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:23:10.520 --> 00:23:12.080 align:middle line:90%
They just define it this way.

00:23:12.080 --> 00:23:14.690 align:middle line:84%
We normally don't give a
name, let's say, in this case.

00:23:14.690 --> 00:23:15.740 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:23:15.740 --> 00:23:18.590 align:middle line:84%
You just specify whether
it's 1 or minus 1.

00:23:18.590 --> 00:23:21.770 align:middle line:84%
And so the reason we
give name for this

00:23:21.770 --> 00:23:23.300 align:middle line:90%
is because of the pion.

00:23:23.300 --> 00:23:26.640 align:middle line:90%
And pions are pseudoscalars.

00:23:26.640 --> 00:23:27.140 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:23:27.140 --> 00:23:29.600 align:middle line:84%
They actually transform
under the parity--

00:23:29.600 --> 00:23:31.580 align:middle line:90%
by minus sign.

00:23:31.580 --> 00:23:37.550 align:middle line:84%
The Higgs would be the ordinary
scalar that transforms as 1.

00:23:37.550 --> 00:23:41.930 align:middle line:90%


00:23:41.930 --> 00:23:43.420 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:23:43.420 --> 00:23:47.540 align:middle line:90%
So if I have this expression--

00:23:47.540 --> 00:23:52.180 align:middle line:84%
so by requiring
UP phi dagger phi

00:23:52.180 --> 00:23:58.660 align:middle line:84%
x UP dagger equal to
that thing-- yeah.

00:23:58.660 --> 00:24:05.530 align:middle line:84%
You could do this, say,
plus-minus eta P phi Px.

00:24:05.530 --> 00:24:10.618 align:middle line:84%
So by requiring this, we can
work out how UP act on a and b.

00:24:10.618 --> 00:24:11.118 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:24:11.118 --> 00:24:14.290 align:middle line:90%


00:24:14.290 --> 00:24:17.980 align:middle line:84%
We can work out how
UP worked on a and b.

00:24:17.980 --> 00:24:21.770 align:middle line:84%
So you find that
the parity acting on

00:24:21.770 --> 00:24:29.890 align:middle line:84%
ak UP dagger equal to
the same eta P factor.

00:24:29.890 --> 00:24:33.275 align:middle line:90%
And then take it to a minus k.

00:24:33.275 --> 00:24:33.775 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:24:33.775 --> 00:24:38.950 align:middle line:84%
So this makes complete
sense because we integrate

00:24:38.950 --> 00:24:40.680 align:middle line:90%
the k as momentum, right?

00:24:40.680 --> 00:24:44.695 align:middle line:84%
So under reflection
of a spatial direction

00:24:44.695 --> 00:24:46.490 align:middle line:84%
your momentum also
change direction.

00:24:46.490 --> 00:24:49.810 align:middle line:84%
And so it takes ak
to get to a minus k.

00:24:49.810 --> 00:24:52.000 align:middle line:84%
And then, similarly,
you can work it

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:59.230 align:middle line:84%
out the UT acting
on ak UT dagger.

00:24:59.230 --> 00:25:04.780 align:middle line:84%
It gives you eta
T, also a minus k.

00:25:04.780 --> 00:25:07.040 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:25:07.040 --> 00:25:08.440 align:middle line:90%
And similarly, with the bk.

00:25:08.440 --> 00:25:08.940 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:25:08.940 --> 00:25:16.610 align:middle line:90%


00:25:16.610 --> 00:25:17.900 align:middle line:90%
So this also makes sense.

00:25:17.900 --> 00:25:19.580 align:middle line:84%
When you reverse
your time direction,

00:25:19.580 --> 00:25:21.290 align:middle line:90%
your momentum also changes sign.

00:25:21.290 --> 00:25:22.010 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:25:22.010 --> 00:25:25.080 align:middle line:90%
Your momentum also changes sign.

00:25:25.080 --> 00:25:29.870 align:middle line:84%
So now the charge conjugation is
a little bit more interesting.

00:25:29.870 --> 00:25:30.370 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:25:30.370 --> 00:25:33.310 align:middle line:84%
So the UC for the
charge conjugation

00:25:33.310 --> 00:25:35.650 align:middle line:84%
is a little bit
more interesting.

00:25:35.650 --> 00:25:43.330 align:middle line:84%
So the charge conjugation
takes ak dagger

00:25:43.330 --> 00:25:46.444 align:middle line:90%
equal to eta C equal to b.

00:25:46.444 --> 00:25:47.308 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:25:47.308 --> 00:25:51.280 align:middle line:90%
And similarly, it takes the--

00:25:51.280 --> 00:25:52.690 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

00:25:52.690 --> 00:25:57.130 align:middle line:84%
So you see that what
charge conjugation does

00:25:57.130 --> 00:26:00.610 align:middle line:84%
is to exchange particle
and antiparticle,

00:26:00.610 --> 00:26:04.660 align:middle line:84%
OK, exchange particle
and antiparticle.

00:26:04.660 --> 00:26:05.210 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:26:05.210 --> 00:26:07.285 align:middle line:84%
Any questions on
this scalar field?

00:26:07.285 --> 00:26:13.760 align:middle line:90%


00:26:13.760 --> 00:26:15.280 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:26:15.280 --> 00:26:17.185 align:middle line:90%
So now let's look at the--

00:26:17.185 --> 00:26:20.110 align:middle line:84%
with this scalar
field story, now we

00:26:20.110 --> 00:26:29.380 align:middle line:84%
can look at a Dirac field,
which is more intricate, OK,

00:26:29.380 --> 00:26:32.240 align:middle line:90%
which is more intricate.

00:26:32.240 --> 00:26:33.655 align:middle line:90%
So let's write down the--

00:26:33.655 --> 00:26:36.410 align:middle line:90%


00:26:36.410 --> 00:26:39.320 align:middle line:84%
so let's forget about
the previous thing.

00:26:39.320 --> 00:26:44.255 align:middle line:84%
Let's write down the action
for the Dirac theory.

00:26:44.255 --> 00:26:52.140 align:middle line:90%


00:26:52.140 --> 00:26:52.640 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:26:52.640 --> 00:26:55.150 align:middle line:84%
And then let's also write
down this equation of motion.

00:26:55.150 --> 00:27:01.550 align:middle line:90%


00:27:01.550 --> 00:27:02.050 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:02.050 --> 00:27:03.600 align:middle line:84%
Now let me call
this equation star

00:27:03.600 --> 00:27:05.080 align:middle line:90%
and erase the earlier star.

00:27:05.080 --> 00:27:08.490 align:middle line:90%


00:27:08.490 --> 00:27:10.950 align:middle line:84%
So now let's first understand
how the parity should

00:27:10.950 --> 00:27:14.390 align:middle line:90%
act on the Dirac field.

00:27:14.390 --> 00:27:16.648 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:27:16.648 --> 00:27:18.940 align:middle line:84%
So now, actually, everything
with the Dirac field story

00:27:18.940 --> 00:27:19.720 align:middle line:90%
becomes tricky.

00:27:19.720 --> 00:27:20.620 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:27:20.620 --> 00:27:22.210 align:middle line:90%
It becomes tricky.

00:27:22.210 --> 00:27:24.940 align:middle line:84%
So naively, if you
wanted to just try

00:27:24.940 --> 00:27:30.280 align:middle line:84%
to generalize the
scalar story, we

00:27:30.280 --> 00:27:33.070 align:middle line:84%
say, let's imagine the Dirac
field should transform.

00:27:33.070 --> 00:27:39.580 align:middle line:90%


00:27:39.580 --> 00:27:40.080 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:27:40.080 --> 00:27:43.890 align:middle line:84%
I'm just-- to say
for the parity,

00:27:43.890 --> 00:27:51.210 align:middle line:84%
for example, psi Px,
OK, with some phase,

00:27:51.210 --> 00:27:54.040 align:middle line:90%
OK, maybe with some phase.

00:27:54.040 --> 00:27:59.130 align:middle line:84%
So we want to naively generalize
to the scalar story, that

00:27:59.130 --> 00:28:01.520 align:middle line:90%
would be what you do.

00:28:01.520 --> 00:28:02.020 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:28:02.020 --> 00:28:04.900 align:middle line:84%
That should be how
the parity transform.

00:28:04.900 --> 00:28:11.770 align:middle line:84%
But now remember psi
now is a four vector.

00:28:11.770 --> 00:28:15.490 align:middle line:84%
Nobody tells you
that, under parity,

00:28:15.490 --> 00:28:18.370 align:middle line:84%
the different component of
this four vector cannot get

00:28:18.370 --> 00:28:20.250 align:middle line:90%
reshuffled.

00:28:20.250 --> 00:28:20.750 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:28:20.750 --> 00:28:22.460 align:middle line:84%
Remember, under Lorentz
transformations,

00:28:22.460 --> 00:28:24.570 align:middle line:90%
they do get reshuffled.

00:28:24.570 --> 00:28:25.070 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:28:25.070 --> 00:28:26.185 align:middle line:84%
In Lorentz
transformations, remember

00:28:26.185 --> 00:28:28.310 align:middle line:84%
that for spinor the Lorentz
transformation not only

00:28:28.310 --> 00:28:33.770 align:middle line:84%
act on x but also on the
internal space of the spinners.

00:28:33.770 --> 00:28:36.650 align:middle line:84%
So you would expect the most
general parity conservation

00:28:36.650 --> 00:28:40.560 align:middle line:84%
should also act on
the internal space.

00:28:40.560 --> 00:28:41.060 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:28:41.060 --> 00:28:43.250 align:middle line:84%
So we would expect the
phase is not enough.

00:28:43.250 --> 00:28:47.746 align:middle line:84%
So we actually have to put
a matrix here and that's

00:28:47.746 --> 00:28:53.430 align:middle line:84%
called D. And whatever phase
will be absorbed in this D. OK?

00:28:53.430 --> 00:28:57.440 align:middle line:84%
Of course, you'll also
include the phase.

00:28:57.440 --> 00:28:58.970 align:middle line:90%
And yeah.

00:28:58.970 --> 00:29:01.160 align:middle line:84%
So for notation
convenience, I will also

00:29:01.160 --> 00:29:10.020 align:middle line:84%
write it as psi prime x
prime equal to D psi x.

00:29:10.020 --> 00:29:10.520 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:29:10.520 --> 00:29:13.650 align:middle line:90%
So the x prime equal to Px.

00:29:13.650 --> 00:29:15.530 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:29:15.530 --> 00:29:17.450 align:middle line:84%
So these two are
the same equation.

00:29:17.450 --> 00:29:18.750 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:29:18.750 --> 00:29:31.605 align:middle line:84%
So you just write, D is a
matrix acting on spinor space.

00:29:31.605 --> 00:29:36.450 align:middle line:90%


00:29:36.450 --> 00:29:38.580 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:29:38.580 --> 00:29:44.650 align:middle line:84%
So in what sense
we say the Dirac

00:29:44.650 --> 00:29:47.840 align:middle line:90%
theory is parity invariant?

00:29:47.840 --> 00:29:48.340 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:29:48.340 --> 00:29:49.840 align:middle line:84%
Let me just
formulate it in terms

00:29:49.840 --> 00:29:51.223 align:middle line:90%
of the equation of motion.

00:29:51.223 --> 00:29:52.890 align:middle line:84%
You can also equivalently
reformulate it

00:29:52.890 --> 00:29:53.950 align:middle line:90%
in terms of the action.

00:29:53.950 --> 00:29:54.790 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:29:54.790 --> 00:29:56.058 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:29:56.058 --> 00:29:58.220 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:29:58.220 --> 00:30:01.220 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Oh, we will
talk about the behavior.

00:30:01.220 --> 00:30:03.050 align:middle line:90%
This is a good question.

00:30:03.050 --> 00:30:04.300 align:middle line:90%
It does not have to.

00:30:04.300 --> 00:30:06.760 align:middle line:84%
And we will talk about
the property of T. Yeah.

00:30:06.760 --> 00:30:11.580 align:middle line:90%


00:30:11.580 --> 00:30:13.020 align:middle line:90%
Do you have other questions?

00:30:13.020 --> 00:30:15.650 align:middle line:90%


00:30:15.650 --> 00:30:16.790 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:30:16.790 --> 00:30:21.870 align:middle line:84%
So what do we mean by the
theory is parity invariant?

00:30:21.870 --> 00:30:22.800 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:30:22.800 --> 00:30:27.540 align:middle line:84%
By the theory-- we say Dirac
theory is parity invariant.

00:30:27.540 --> 00:30:31.110 align:middle line:90%


00:30:31.110 --> 00:30:35.560 align:middle line:84%
We say if Dirac theory
have a parity symmetry,

00:30:35.560 --> 00:30:37.650 align:middle line:84%
you can always define
a parity operation.

00:30:37.650 --> 00:30:41.920 align:middle line:84%
So when we say Dirac equation
have a parity symmetry,

00:30:41.920 --> 00:30:46.570 align:middle line:84%
it means that if we
start with a psi which

00:30:46.570 --> 00:30:51.480 align:middle line:84%
satisfies the Dirac
equation, and then there

00:30:51.480 --> 00:31:03.810 align:middle line:84%
should exist such a D, such a
matrix, such a transformation

00:31:03.810 --> 00:31:18.680 align:middle line:84%
so that at this
transformed psi still

00:31:18.680 --> 00:31:24.000 align:middle line:84%
satisfies the Dirac equation
but in the reflected space.

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:24.500 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:31:24.500 --> 00:31:27.320 align:middle line:90%
So you want to reflect.

00:31:27.320 --> 00:31:32.550 align:middle line:84%
So x prime goes right
into the reflected space.

00:31:32.550 --> 00:31:37.685 align:middle line:84%
And as we say the theory
have a parity symmetry-- it

00:31:37.685 --> 00:31:41.460 align:middle line:84%
means in the reflected space you
should have the same equation.

00:31:41.460 --> 00:31:41.960 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:31:41.960 --> 00:31:44.040 align:middle line:84%
You should have the same
form of the equation.

00:31:44.040 --> 00:31:48.200 align:middle line:84%
So that means that this psi
prime, when you're writing it

00:31:48.200 --> 00:31:50.540 align:middle line:84%
in the reflected
space, should have

00:31:50.540 --> 00:31:54.360 align:middle line:84%
the same form of the equation
as the original Dirac equation.

00:31:54.360 --> 00:31:58.370 align:middle line:84%
So this is the same concept
as this Lorentz covariance

00:31:58.370 --> 00:31:59.480 align:middle line:90%
we described earlier.

00:31:59.480 --> 00:32:00.920 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:32:00.920 --> 00:32:01.990 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:32:01.990 --> 00:32:04.532 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Why doesn't the parity
transform the gamma matrices

00:32:04.532 --> 00:32:06.530 align:middle line:90%
matrices?

00:32:06.530 --> 00:32:10.095 align:middle line:84%
Because we changed d
mu but not the gamma?

00:32:10.095 --> 00:32:10.970 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah, yeah.

00:32:10.970 --> 00:32:12.750 align:middle line:84%
Gamma matrix is
just some numbers.

00:32:12.750 --> 00:32:13.250 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:32:13.250 --> 00:32:15.730 align:middle line:84%
Because the gamma matrix is
always just some numbers.

00:32:15.730 --> 00:32:17.390 align:middle line:90%
They're not spacetime variables.

00:32:17.390 --> 00:32:20.875 align:middle line:84%
And so they're not-- so they
don't change under the parity.

00:32:20.875 --> 00:32:23.710 align:middle line:90%


00:32:23.710 --> 00:32:25.350 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:32:25.350 --> 00:32:26.450 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:32:26.450 --> 00:32:29.910 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Is there any reason
why D has to be a matrix?

00:32:29.910 --> 00:32:31.282 align:middle line:90%
Why does it have to be linear?

00:32:31.282 --> 00:32:31.990 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: No, no.

00:32:31.990 --> 00:32:33.300 align:middle line:90%
D does not have to be a matrix.

00:32:33.300 --> 00:32:36.690 align:middle line:84%
It's just that D
can be a matrix.

00:32:36.690 --> 00:32:40.520 align:middle line:84%
But we want to find the
D so that we have this.

00:32:40.520 --> 00:32:41.576 align:middle line:90%
But D can be identity.

00:32:41.576 --> 00:32:43.576 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Could it be
some complicated function,

00:32:43.576 --> 00:32:44.340 align:middle line:90%
like non-linear?

00:32:44.340 --> 00:32:47.800 align:middle line:84%
Because we already
allowed for non-linear,

00:32:47.800 --> 00:32:52.202 align:middle line:84%
like, time reversal
operators [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:52.202 --> 00:32:52.910 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: No, no.

00:32:52.910 --> 00:32:55.580 align:middle line:84%
The time reversal
is linear, right?

00:32:55.580 --> 00:32:56.780 align:middle line:90%
Time reversal is linear.

00:32:56.780 --> 00:32:58.355 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Antilinear.

00:32:58.355 --> 00:32:58.980 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

00:32:58.980 --> 00:33:02.270 align:middle line:90%


00:33:02.270 --> 00:33:04.020 align:middle line:90%
The action of a--

00:33:04.020 --> 00:33:07.620 align:middle line:90%
normally, action of a--

00:33:07.620 --> 00:33:11.070 align:middle line:90%
yeah, this kind of--

00:33:11.070 --> 00:33:13.180 align:middle line:90%
just go to psi itself.

00:33:13.180 --> 00:33:16.355 align:middle line:90%
But you can-- yeah.

00:33:16.355 --> 00:33:19.460 align:middle line:90%


00:33:19.460 --> 00:33:21.565 align:middle line:90%
You're asking why not--

00:33:21.565 --> 00:33:25.840 align:middle line:84%
why we don't use a
psi squared term?

00:33:25.840 --> 00:33:31.908 align:middle line:84%
Or you are asking whether the
D can depend on spacetime?

00:33:31.908 --> 00:33:32.950 align:middle line:90%
Which one are you asking?

00:33:32.950 --> 00:33:33.575 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:33:33.575 --> 00:33:36.705 align:middle line:84%
I mean, psi-- like, some
arbitrary function of psi.

00:33:36.705 --> 00:33:37.330 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

00:33:37.330 --> 00:33:38.740 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, but this is
the simplest one.

00:33:38.740 --> 00:33:39.240 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:33:39.240 --> 00:33:43.660 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, if we can make this work,
then you don't have to do that.

00:33:43.660 --> 00:33:44.160 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:33:44.160 --> 00:33:45.810 align:middle line:90%
You do the simplest one first.

00:33:45.810 --> 00:33:51.690 align:middle line:90%


00:33:51.690 --> 00:33:55.290 align:middle line:84%
Also, we do believe that
this kind of parity operation

00:33:55.290 --> 00:33:57.550 align:middle line:90%
should be a linear operation.

00:33:57.550 --> 00:33:58.050 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:33:58.050 --> 00:34:01.230 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, if you add the
two operators together,

00:34:01.230 --> 00:34:05.040 align:middle line:84%
you do the parity,
and you should--

00:34:05.040 --> 00:34:08.290 align:middle line:84%
after you do the parity should
be still summed together.

00:34:08.290 --> 00:34:10.170 align:middle line:84%
If it's a non-linear
function, then you

00:34:10.170 --> 00:34:11.820 align:middle line:90%
won't satisfy that property.

00:34:11.820 --> 00:34:12.480 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:34:12.480 --> 00:34:14.909 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, just from our
experience, the--

00:34:14.909 --> 00:34:17.010 align:middle line:84%
yeah, just physically,
we expect the parity

00:34:17.010 --> 00:34:18.337 align:middle line:90%
to be a linear operation.

00:34:18.337 --> 00:34:21.080 align:middle line:90%


00:34:21.080 --> 00:34:22.330 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:34:22.330 --> 00:34:22.960 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:22.960 --> 00:34:26.150 align:middle line:84%
So we want to find the D
so that this is satisfied.

00:34:26.150 --> 00:34:26.650 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:34:26.650 --> 00:34:29.650 align:middle line:90%
So that means that the--

00:34:29.650 --> 00:34:30.580 align:middle line:90%
so this is easy.

00:34:30.580 --> 00:34:33.290 align:middle line:84%
So now let's just look
at this equation a bit.

00:34:33.290 --> 00:34:33.790 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:34:33.790 --> 00:34:36.919 align:middle line:84%
So let's write it
more explicitly.

00:34:36.919 --> 00:34:39.909 align:middle line:90%


00:34:39.909 --> 00:34:42.469 align:middle line:90%
So partial mu prime--

00:34:42.469 --> 00:34:42.969 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

00:34:42.969 --> 00:34:44.900 align:middle line:90%
So we write this explicitly.

00:34:44.900 --> 00:34:49.239 align:middle line:84%
So partial 0 prime is the same
as the original partial prime

00:34:49.239 --> 00:34:52.540 align:middle line:84%
because you don't flip
the time direction.

00:34:52.540 --> 00:34:53.080 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:34:53.080 --> 00:34:55.580 align:middle line:84%
And then you flip the
spatial direction.

00:34:55.580 --> 00:34:58.040 align:middle line:84%
So that means this becomes
a partial i, partial i --

00:34:58.040 --> 00:34:59.170 align:middle line:90%
gamma i partial i.

00:34:59.170 --> 00:35:03.100 align:middle line:84%
And so I remove the prime, but
I have a minus sign here, OK,

00:35:03.100 --> 00:35:05.470 align:middle line:90%
because you've changed signs.

00:35:05.470 --> 00:35:08.680 align:middle line:90%
And the minus n--

00:35:08.680 --> 00:35:12.800 align:middle line:84%
and this one from our definition
should be equal to this.

00:35:12.800 --> 00:35:18.910 align:middle line:84%
So this is just equal
to D psi x equal to 0.

00:35:18.910 --> 00:35:19.410 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:35:19.410 --> 00:35:25.680 align:middle line:90%


00:35:25.680 --> 00:35:26.180 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:35:26.180 --> 00:35:29.150 align:middle line:90%


00:35:29.150 --> 00:35:32.840 align:middle line:84%
So now if you compare
with this equation--

00:35:32.840 --> 00:35:37.580 align:middle line:84%
so the-- so now if you
compare with this equation,

00:35:37.580 --> 00:35:41.810 align:middle line:84%
now let's add the
D on this equation.

00:35:41.810 --> 00:35:46.090 align:middle line:84%
So that corresponding
to D-- gamma 0 partial 0

00:35:46.090 --> 00:35:51.880 align:middle line:84%
plus gamma i partial i
minus m psi x equal to 0.

00:35:51.880 --> 00:35:52.380 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:35:52.380 --> 00:35:54.460 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
original equation.

00:35:54.460 --> 00:35:57.310 align:middle line:84%
And now we want these two
equations to be equivalent.

00:35:57.310 --> 00:35:57.810 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:35:57.810 --> 00:36:00.227 align:middle line:84%
Because given this equation,
we should have that equation.

00:36:00.227 --> 00:36:00.750 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:36:00.750 --> 00:36:03.850 align:middle line:84%
And so we want these two
equation to be equivalent.

00:36:03.850 --> 00:36:06.113 align:middle line:84%
So in order for them
to be equivalent,

00:36:06.113 --> 00:36:07.530 align:middle line:84%
you see the last
term is the same.

00:36:07.530 --> 00:36:10.545 align:middle line:84%
Because the m is just a
number that commutes with D.

00:36:10.545 --> 00:36:12.920 align:middle line:84%
And then in order for these
two equations to be the same,

00:36:12.920 --> 00:36:14.630 align:middle line:90%
