00:49:58.800 --> 00:50:01.140 align:middle line:84%
That will account
for the extra minus.

00:50:01.140 --> 00:50:05.700 align:middle line:84%
So if you know C, then you
also know this time translation

00:50:05.700 --> 00:50:06.865 align:middle line:90%
symmetry matrix.

00:50:06.865 --> 00:50:07.365 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:50:07.365 --> 00:50:12.570 align:middle line:90%


00:50:12.570 --> 00:50:13.290 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:50:13.290 --> 00:50:16.435 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:50:16.435 --> 00:50:17.310 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah, yeah.

00:50:17.310 --> 00:50:21.030 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, because of the--
only the operator itself,

00:50:21.030 --> 00:50:23.340 align:middle line:90%
only U is anti-linear.

00:50:23.340 --> 00:50:24.400 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:50:24.400 --> 00:50:26.700 align:middle line:84%
t just goes right into
the specific matrix

00:50:26.700 --> 00:50:28.310 align:middle line:90%
acting on the spinner space.

00:50:28.310 --> 00:50:30.508 align:middle line:84%
And so that's just
an ordinary matrix.

00:50:30.508 --> 00:50:32.420 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:50:32.420 --> 00:50:34.760 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, DT is just
ordinary numbers.

00:50:34.760 --> 00:50:36.520 align:middle line:84%
They're made up from
the gamma matrices.

00:50:36.520 --> 00:50:37.020 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:50:37.020 --> 00:50:39.780 align:middle line:90%


00:50:39.780 --> 00:50:42.610 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:50:42.610 --> 00:50:43.300 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:50:43.300 --> 00:50:44.770 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So is
parity a response

00:50:44.770 --> 00:50:46.245 align:middle line:90%
to the reflections in space?

00:50:46.245 --> 00:50:46.870 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

00:50:46.870 --> 00:50:49.030 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: And time reversal--
is that a reflection in time?

00:50:49.030 --> 00:50:49.655 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

00:50:49.655 --> 00:50:57.090 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So can you,
like, boost into spacetime?

00:50:57.090 --> 00:51:00.960 align:middle line:84%
If you make a Lorentz boost,
could space reflections then--

00:51:00.960 --> 00:51:01.600 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: No.

00:51:01.600 --> 00:51:03.630 align:middle line:84%
No, they cannot
relate these two.

00:51:03.630 --> 00:51:06.568 align:middle line:84%
They are independent,
discrete transformations.

00:51:06.568 --> 00:51:07.860 align:middle line:90%
They're not related to a boost.

00:51:07.860 --> 00:51:09.047 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:51:09.047 --> 00:51:10.380 align:middle line:90%
They are not related by a boost.

00:51:10.380 --> 00:51:12.750 align:middle line:90%


00:51:12.750 --> 00:51:14.250 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, if they're
related by a boost,

00:51:14.250 --> 00:51:19.620 align:middle line:84%
then we should only need
to worry about one of them.

00:51:19.620 --> 00:51:22.530 align:middle line:84%
Because the boost we
already understood.

00:51:22.530 --> 00:51:24.070 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:51:24.070 --> 00:51:24.570 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:51:24.570 --> 00:51:27.960 align:middle line:84%
So they are independent
discrete transformations.

00:51:27.960 --> 00:51:32.220 align:middle line:84%
They are not related
by any other continuous

00:51:32.220 --> 00:51:33.388 align:middle line:90%
transformation.

00:51:33.388 --> 00:51:36.980 align:middle line:90%


00:51:36.980 --> 00:51:39.480 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:51:39.480 --> 00:51:40.140 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:51:40.140 --> 00:51:42.515 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: There is only
one parity transformation

00:51:42.515 --> 00:51:44.522 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE].

00:51:44.522 --> 00:51:45.730 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah, that's right.

00:51:45.730 --> 00:51:46.930 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:51:46.930 --> 00:51:48.760 align:middle line:84%
Just in any dimension,
you have just one.

00:51:48.760 --> 00:51:49.260 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:51:49.260 --> 00:51:54.133 align:middle line:90%


00:51:54.133 --> 00:51:54.880 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:51:54.880 --> 00:51:56.980 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:51:56.980 --> 00:51:58.210 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:58.210 --> 00:51:59.050 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:51:59.050 --> 00:52:01.092 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I don't
know if this makes sense.

00:52:01.092 --> 00:52:04.945 align:middle line:84%
But is it possible to have a
situation where in one frame

00:52:04.945 --> 00:52:09.612 align:middle line:84%
a quantity is conserved
through parity or time reversal

00:52:09.612 --> 00:52:12.550 align:middle line:84%
transform, but then in
a Lorentz boosted frame

00:52:12.550 --> 00:52:15.704 align:middle line:84%
it's different than
what [INAUDIBLE]

00:52:15.704 --> 00:52:18.590 align:middle line:84%
or if it's conserved in
one, it's conserved in all?

00:52:18.590 --> 00:52:23.255 align:middle line:90%


00:52:23.255 --> 00:52:23.880 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

00:52:23.880 --> 00:52:24.380 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:52:24.380 --> 00:52:27.270 align:middle line:90%


00:52:27.270 --> 00:52:29.840 align:middle line:84%
If it's conserved in one,
it's conserved in all of them.

00:52:29.840 --> 00:52:32.090 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, it's because the
conservation equation

00:52:32.090 --> 00:52:34.370 align:middle line:90%
is a covariant equation.

00:52:34.370 --> 00:52:37.871 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, because the conservation
equation is partial mu,

00:52:37.871 --> 00:52:39.980 align:middle line:90%
J mu mu equal to 0.

00:52:39.980 --> 00:52:42.530 align:middle line:84%
So this equation have the
same form in any frame.

00:52:42.530 --> 00:52:43.460 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:52:43.460 --> 00:52:47.330 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, but the charge is
different in different frame.

00:52:47.330 --> 00:52:49.610 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, they're related
by the transformation.

00:52:49.610 --> 00:52:52.463 align:middle line:84%
Just in any frame, you can
define a conserved charge.

00:52:52.463 --> 00:52:52.963 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:52:52.963 --> 00:52:57.220 align:middle line:90%


00:52:57.220 --> 00:52:58.980 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:52:58.980 --> 00:53:00.270 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:53:00.270 --> 00:53:03.210 align:middle line:84%
So now let's move on
to the next topic.

00:53:03.210 --> 00:53:07.060 align:middle line:90%


00:53:07.060 --> 00:53:10.738 align:middle line:84%
So now, finally, we'll
talk about path integrals

00:53:10.738 --> 00:53:11.280 align:middle line:90%
for fermions.

00:53:11.280 --> 00:53:15.000 align:middle line:90%


00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:17.830 align:middle line:84%
And with path integrals,
then we can do interactions.

00:53:17.830 --> 00:53:18.330 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:53:18.330 --> 00:53:21.750 align:middle line:84%
Remember, when we know how to
do path integrals for scalar,

00:53:21.750 --> 00:53:23.520 align:middle line:84%
then we can easily
do interactions.

00:53:23.520 --> 00:53:26.070 align:middle line:84%
And now let's do the path
integral for fermion.

00:53:26.070 --> 00:53:30.510 align:middle line:84%
And then that will give
us a very simple way

00:53:30.510 --> 00:53:32.695 align:middle line:90%
to treat interacting theories.

00:53:32.695 --> 00:53:33.195 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:53:33.195 --> 00:53:38.210 align:middle line:90%


00:53:38.210 --> 00:53:48.140 align:middle line:84%
So let's just recall in the path
integral we considered before--

00:53:48.140 --> 00:53:50.410 align:middle line:84%
so if you have ordinary
quantum mechanics--

00:53:50.410 --> 00:53:53.600 align:middle line:90%


00:53:53.600 --> 00:54:01.690 align:middle line:84%
so you have x and the p
commutator equal to i.

00:54:01.690 --> 00:54:04.900 align:middle line:84%
And then the path integral,
you just integrate over

00:54:04.900 --> 00:54:08.980 align:middle line:90%
all configurations of xt.

00:54:08.980 --> 00:54:09.640 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:54:09.640 --> 00:54:12.140 align:middle line:84%
So that's what you do
in quantum mechanics.

00:54:12.140 --> 00:54:15.590 align:middle line:84%
So now xt is just an
ordinary function.

00:54:15.590 --> 00:54:16.090 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:54:16.090 --> 00:54:18.730 align:middle line:84%
You just integrate over
all possible trajectories.

00:54:18.730 --> 00:54:22.570 align:middle line:84%
And xt is just an
ordinary function.

00:54:22.570 --> 00:54:27.160 align:middle line:84%
So now when we go to
quantum field theory,

00:54:27.160 --> 00:54:32.550 align:middle line:84%
then we have phi
then commute with--

00:54:32.550 --> 00:54:34.170 align:middle line:90%
yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:54:34.170 --> 00:54:37.498 align:middle line:84%
So let me just put a hat
just to show, to emphasize

00:54:37.498 --> 00:54:38.790 align:middle line:90%
that this is our operator here.

00:54:38.790 --> 00:54:42.270 align:middle line:90%
And the phi-- we have tx.

00:54:42.270 --> 00:54:46.305 align:middle line:84%
And then we have pi phi,
the conjugate momentum.

00:54:46.305 --> 00:54:48.940 align:middle line:90%


00:54:48.940 --> 00:54:51.730 align:middle line:84%
And again, this is equal
to i something, OK--

00:54:51.730 --> 00:54:52.565 align:middle line:90%
the delta function.

00:54:52.565 --> 00:54:53.065 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:54:53.065 --> 00:54:57.210 align:middle line:90%


00:54:57.210 --> 00:54:57.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:54:57.780 --> 00:54:58.660 align:middle line:90%
This is i.

00:54:58.660 --> 00:55:01.565 align:middle line:84%
And then you have
delta function.

00:55:01.565 --> 00:55:03.190 align:middle line:84%
And then when you do
the path integral,

00:55:03.190 --> 00:55:06.060 align:middle line:84%
you just integrate over all
configurations of phi xt.

00:55:06.060 --> 00:55:08.920 align:middle line:90%


00:55:08.920 --> 00:55:12.380 align:middle line:84%
And now this is just
a classical field.

00:55:12.380 --> 00:55:14.930 align:middle line:84%
Now, essentially, you view this
just as an ordinary function.

00:55:14.930 --> 00:55:15.470 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:55:15.470 --> 00:55:18.260 align:middle line:84%
You integrate just all
possible values of it,

00:55:18.260 --> 00:55:19.880 align:middle line:84%
OK, all possible
functions of it,

00:55:19.880 --> 00:55:22.070 align:middle line:84%
OK, all possible
functions of phi.

00:55:22.070 --> 00:55:24.860 align:middle line:90%


00:55:24.860 --> 00:55:27.930 align:middle line:90%
So now we have to do fermions.

00:55:27.930 --> 00:55:30.420 align:middle line:90%
We have to do psi.

00:55:30.420 --> 00:55:33.390 align:middle line:90%
So psi is a little bit weird.

00:55:33.390 --> 00:55:36.030 align:middle line:84%
Because as we discussed
before, the psi--

00:55:36.030 --> 00:55:37.860 align:middle line:84%
we no longer have
the commutator.

00:55:37.860 --> 00:55:40.320 align:middle line:84%
You actually have
an anti-commutator.

00:55:40.320 --> 00:55:41.400 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:55:41.400 --> 00:55:43.480 align:middle line:90%
So what do you do?

00:55:43.480 --> 00:55:43.980 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:55:43.980 --> 00:55:46.410 align:middle line:84%
Do you still just
follow the same rule,

00:55:46.410 --> 00:55:49.080 align:middle line:84%
or do you actually have
to change the rule?

00:55:49.080 --> 00:55:50.100 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:55:50.100 --> 00:55:54.510 align:middle line:84%
So that actually was
a question which--

00:55:54.510 --> 00:55:58.950 align:middle line:84%
so Feynman actually-- he came
up with this idea of the path

00:55:58.950 --> 00:56:02.870 align:middle line:90%
integral in 1948.

00:56:02.870 --> 00:56:05.030 align:middle line:84%
And then, of course,
generalization to scalar

00:56:05.030 --> 00:56:05.940 align:middle line:90%
will be immediate.

00:56:05.940 --> 00:56:07.380 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:56:07.380 --> 00:56:11.180 align:middle line:84%
But then he wanted to
generalize to fermions.

00:56:11.180 --> 00:56:13.890 align:middle line:84%
But then for a long
time, he couldn't do it.

00:56:13.890 --> 00:56:17.040 align:middle line:84%
And if you just use this
method to do for fermions--

00:56:17.040 --> 00:56:18.910 align:middle line:90%
and they just didn't work.

00:56:18.910 --> 00:56:19.410 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:56:19.410 --> 00:56:23.150 align:middle line:84%
We will not go
through that exercise.

00:56:23.150 --> 00:56:26.230 align:middle line:84%
If you does this for fermion,
it just does not work.

00:56:26.230 --> 00:56:29.130 align:middle line:84%
So for many years, he
couldn't find the answer.

00:56:29.130 --> 00:56:32.100 align:middle line:90%
But then around the 1962--

00:56:32.100 --> 00:56:34.530 align:middle line:90%
I think it's 1962 or 1965.

00:56:34.530 --> 00:56:38.985 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, just around
some early 1960s,

00:56:38.985 --> 00:56:42.030 align:middle line:84%
a former Soviet
physicist actually

00:56:42.030 --> 00:56:45.830 align:middle line:84%
came up with a brilliant idea
to solve this problem, OK--

00:56:45.830 --> 00:56:50.370 align:middle line:84%
and, like, 15 years later after
the discovery of path integral.

00:56:50.370 --> 00:56:55.640 align:middle line:84%
And so the basic idea is that
when you have a Dirac field--

00:56:55.640 --> 00:57:27.240 align:middle line:90%


00:57:27.240 --> 00:57:33.510 align:middle line:84%
so when you have a
Dirac field, then you

00:57:33.510 --> 00:57:35.250 align:middle line:90%
have anti-commutation relation.

00:57:35.250 --> 00:57:40.825 align:middle line:84%
psi and pi psi is an
anti-commutation relation.

00:57:40.825 --> 00:57:41.325 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:57:41.325 --> 00:57:43.920 align:middle line:90%


00:57:43.920 --> 00:57:47.320 align:middle line:90%
It's an anti-commutator.

00:57:47.320 --> 00:57:50.530 align:middle line:84%
And then this guy
called Berezin.

00:57:50.530 --> 00:57:53.800 align:middle line:84%
Berezin then postulates
that, when you

00:57:53.800 --> 00:57:55.360 align:middle line:90%
do the path integral, what is--

00:57:55.360 --> 00:57:58.570 align:middle line:84%
in the path integral will be an
analog of the classical version

00:57:58.570 --> 00:58:02.660 align:middle line:84%
of this field, OK, the classical
version of this operator.

00:58:02.660 --> 00:58:04.540 align:middle line:84%
So then what would be
the classical version

00:58:04.540 --> 00:58:07.530 align:middle line:90%
of this anti-commutator?

00:58:07.530 --> 00:58:11.310 align:middle line:84%
And he had just written it just
should be some quantities which

00:58:11.310 --> 00:58:12.790 align:middle line:90%
anti-commute.

00:58:12.790 --> 00:58:13.290 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:58:13.290 --> 00:58:19.920 align:middle line:84%
So when we say classical,
we put it in quotes

00:58:19.920 --> 00:58:23.083 align:middle line:84%
because we only do this
in the path integral.

00:58:23.083 --> 00:58:24.750 align:middle line:84%
And we're then, of
course, corresponding

00:58:24.750 --> 00:58:33.200 align:middle line:84%
to anti-commuting
fields, objects.

00:58:33.200 --> 00:58:34.405 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:58:34.405 --> 00:58:36.030 align:middle line:84%
And then when you do
the path integral,

00:58:36.030 --> 00:58:39.780 align:middle line:90%
you just integrate over psi.

00:58:39.780 --> 00:58:41.800 align:middle line:84%
But psi is an
anti-commuting object.

00:58:41.800 --> 00:58:42.300 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:58:42.300 --> 00:58:44.717 align:middle line:84%
It turns out that this just
brilliantly solve the problem.

00:58:44.717 --> 00:58:45.440 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:58:45.440 --> 00:58:46.530 align:middle line:90%
It just immediately works.

00:58:46.530 --> 00:58:47.238 align:middle line:90%
It's very simple.

00:58:47.238 --> 00:58:49.900 align:middle line:90%


00:58:49.900 --> 00:58:52.090 align:middle line:84%
So in hindsight, it's
extremely simple.

00:58:52.090 --> 00:58:55.240 align:middle line:84%
But actually, Feynman couldn't
figure it out himself.

00:58:55.240 --> 00:58:56.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:56.130 --> 00:58:58.790 align:middle line:90%
[LIGHT CHUCKLE] Right.

00:58:58.790 --> 00:59:01.730 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, so now let's
talk a little bit

00:59:01.730 --> 00:59:04.950 align:middle line:84%
about this
anti-commuting object.

00:59:04.950 --> 00:59:05.450 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:59:05.450 --> 00:59:08.450 align:middle line:84%
So these are called the
Grassmann variables or numbers.

00:59:08.450 --> 00:59:22.770 align:middle line:90%


00:59:22.770 --> 00:59:28.720 align:middle line:84%
So this Grassmann object,
they just anti-commutes.

00:59:28.720 --> 00:59:30.380 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:59:30.380 --> 00:59:35.760 align:middle line:84%
So they even anti-commute
with themself.

00:59:35.760 --> 00:59:39.520 align:middle line:84%
So if you anti-commute with
yourself, then the only thing

00:59:39.520 --> 00:59:42.560 align:middle line:84%
you can have is a theta
square that must be 0.

00:59:42.560 --> 00:59:43.060 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:59:43.060 --> 00:59:45.160 align:middle line:84%
If you have anti-commuting
object theta,

00:59:45.160 --> 00:59:46.600 align:middle line:84%
and you can
anti-commute yourself,

00:59:46.600 --> 00:59:47.688 align:middle line:90%
it will be equal to 0.

00:59:47.688 --> 00:59:50.230 align:middle line:84%
Because theta-squared should be
equal to minus theta-squared.

00:59:50.230 --> 00:59:53.110 align:middle line:84%
And then, of course,
it can only be 0.

00:59:53.110 --> 00:59:56.800 align:middle line:84%
And so if you have two such
objects, theta and eta--

00:59:56.800 --> 01:00:00.750 align:middle line:90%
and then equal to minus eta.

01:00:00.750 --> 01:00:03.880 align:middle line:84%
And of course, eta-squared
should also be 0.

01:00:03.880 --> 01:00:04.380 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:00:04.380 --> 01:00:08.300 align:middle line:90%


01:00:08.300 --> 01:00:12.110 align:middle line:84%
So this kind of property
make this kind of object

01:00:12.110 --> 01:00:13.690 align:middle line:90%
very simple.

01:00:13.690 --> 01:00:17.240 align:middle line:84%
So now we can also talk about
the functions of such objects.

01:00:17.240 --> 01:00:17.740 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:00:17.740 --> 01:00:20.060 align:middle line:84%
We can also talk about the
function of such objects.

01:00:20.060 --> 01:00:26.140 align:middle line:84%
Say, if we have a
function f of theta--

01:00:26.140 --> 01:00:26.890 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:00:26.890 --> 01:00:34.210 align:middle line:84%
So we define the function in
terms of the power series.

01:00:34.210 --> 01:00:36.650 align:middle line:90%
So suppose that we have an x--

01:00:36.650 --> 01:00:39.450 align:middle line:84%
say, if you write down a
Gaussian function or whatever

01:00:39.450 --> 01:00:44.200 align:middle line:84%
function, we define this
function by the power series.

01:00:44.200 --> 01:00:47.310 align:middle line:84%
So power series means
that to zeroth order,

01:00:47.310 --> 01:00:53.250 align:middle line:84%
we have f0 corresponding
to theta equal to 0,

01:00:53.250 --> 01:00:57.510 align:middle line:90%
and then you have f1 theta.

01:00:57.510 --> 01:00:58.500 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:00:58.500 --> 01:01:01.920 align:middle line:84%
But now if you look at
f2 theta, theta-squared--

01:01:01.920 --> 01:01:03.180 align:middle line:90%
that would be 0.

01:01:03.180 --> 01:01:05.520 align:middle line:84%
So all higher-order
terms can be 0.

01:01:05.520 --> 01:01:08.490 align:middle line:90%
So you only have two terms.

01:01:08.490 --> 01:01:09.000 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:10.620 align:middle line:84%
So the only function
of this variable

01:01:10.620 --> 01:01:13.380 align:middle line:84%
will have two, terms, the
constant term and the term

01:01:13.380 --> 01:01:15.960 align:middle line:90%
proportional to theta.

01:01:15.960 --> 01:01:19.180 align:middle line:84%
And then the functions of such
variables are very simple.

01:01:19.180 --> 01:01:21.230 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:01:21.230 --> 01:01:27.200 align:middle line:84%
And if you have two variables,
theta 1 and theta 2,

01:01:27.200 --> 01:01:30.680 align:middle line:84%
then you just expand
until you encounter--

01:01:30.680 --> 01:01:37.805 align:middle line:84%
you have f0 plus f1
theta 1 plus f2 theta

01:01:37.805 --> 01:01:43.670 align:middle line:90%
2 then plus f12 theta 1 theta 2.

01:01:43.670 --> 01:01:44.690 align:middle line:90%
That's it.

01:01:44.690 --> 01:01:46.280 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:01:46.280 --> 01:01:46.780 align:middle line:90%
That's it.

01:01:46.780 --> 01:01:48.155 align:middle line:84%
Because for any
other term we are

01:01:48.155 --> 01:01:50.620 align:middle line:84%
involving either theta
1-squared or theta 2-squared,

01:01:50.620 --> 01:01:51.280 align:middle line:90%
that will be 0.

01:01:51.280 --> 01:01:55.110 align:middle line:90%


01:01:55.110 --> 01:01:59.540 align:middle line:84%
So the differentiation
will be extremely simple.

01:01:59.540 --> 01:02:01.690 align:middle line:84%
So if you're taking
d f theta d theta--

01:02:01.690 --> 01:02:04.510 align:middle line:90%


01:02:04.510 --> 01:02:06.987 align:middle line:84%
so you just-- because
this is the constant.

01:02:06.987 --> 01:02:08.320 align:middle line:90%
And so this is just equal to f1.

01:02:08.320 --> 01:02:12.010 align:middle line:90%


01:02:12.010 --> 01:02:13.000 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:18.340 align:middle line:84%
But the one thing-- you
do have to be careful

01:02:18.340 --> 01:02:20.485 align:middle line:84%
when you have this
multiple-variable function.

01:02:20.485 --> 01:02:23.000 align:middle line:90%


01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:24.740 align:middle line:84%
And then it actually
matters whether you

01:02:24.740 --> 01:02:26.390 align:middle line:84%
take the derivative
from the left

01:02:26.390 --> 01:02:29.060 align:middle line:84%
or take the derivative
from the right.

01:02:29.060 --> 01:02:30.090 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:02:30.090 --> 01:02:34.660 align:middle line:84%
The direction you take the
derivative becomes important.

01:02:34.660 --> 01:02:35.160 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:02:35.160 --> 01:02:42.970 align:middle line:84%
So for example, if we take
the derivative-- yeah.

01:02:42.970 --> 01:02:44.240 align:middle line:90%
Let me do it here.

01:02:44.240 --> 01:02:47.980 align:middle line:84%
So if you, from the left,
take the derivative f theta

01:02:47.980 --> 01:02:55.980 align:middle line:84%
1 on this f theta 1, theta
2, and then this term is 0.

01:02:55.980 --> 01:02:58.890 align:middle line:90%
This term gives us f1.

01:02:58.890 --> 01:03:01.378 align:middle line:84%
This term does not
depend on theta 1.

01:03:01.378 --> 01:03:03.670 align:middle line:84%
And so this term is also 0
when we take the derivative.

01:03:03.670 --> 01:03:05.220 align:middle line:90%
And here, we have theta 1.

01:03:05.220 --> 01:03:08.920 align:middle line:90%
So we just get f12 theta 2.

01:03:08.920 --> 01:03:09.420 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:03:09.420 --> 01:03:12.780 align:middle line:84%
So this is derivative
from the left.

01:03:12.780 --> 01:03:24.615 align:middle line:84%
But now if I take the derivative
from the right, theta 1, OK--

01:03:24.615 --> 01:03:29.240 align:middle line:90%


01:03:29.240 --> 01:03:33.250 align:middle line:84%
so this arrow means you take
the derivative from the right.

01:03:33.250 --> 01:03:35.220 align:middle line:84%
And again, the same
thing for this one.

01:03:35.220 --> 01:03:35.970 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't matter.

01:03:35.970 --> 01:03:37.500 align:middle line:90%
There's only one theta 1.

01:03:37.500 --> 01:03:39.300 align:middle line:90%
So you just get f1.

01:03:39.300 --> 01:03:41.130 align:middle line:90%
Again, these two will be 0.

01:03:41.130 --> 01:03:44.430 align:middle line:84%
But now if we take the
derivative from the right,

01:03:44.430 --> 01:03:47.430 align:middle line:84%
then you have to move theta
1 to the right of theta 2

01:03:47.430 --> 01:03:49.000 align:middle line:84%
first because there's
a theta 2 here.

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:50.542 align:middle line:84%
And then that gives
you a minus sign.

01:03:50.542 --> 01:03:54.000 align:middle line:90%
So it will give you f12 theta 2.

01:03:54.000 --> 01:03:56.160 align:middle line:90%
So you differ by a minus sign.

01:03:56.160 --> 01:03:57.330 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:03:57.330 --> 01:04:01.620 align:middle line:84%
So from now on, without
specifically mentioning,

01:04:01.620 --> 01:04:03.340 align:middle line:84%
we always take
derivative from the left.

01:04:03.340 --> 01:04:04.042 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:04:04.042 --> 01:04:05.500 align:middle line:84%
So the convention
is we always take

01:04:05.500 --> 01:04:06.625 align:middle line:90%
the derivative of the left.

01:04:06.625 --> 01:04:07.499 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:04:07.499 --> 01:04:11.563 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:04:11.563 --> 01:04:12.230 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Sorry?

01:04:12.230 --> 01:04:15.140 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
coefficient [INAUDIBLE] f0

01:04:15.140 --> 01:04:16.600 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE]

01:04:16.600 --> 01:04:17.555 align:middle line:90%


01:04:17.555 --> 01:04:18.680 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: What do you mean?

01:04:18.680 --> 01:04:20.120 align:middle line:90%
Like, what type of object?

01:04:20.120 --> 01:04:22.340 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Like, [INAUDIBLE]

01:04:22.340 --> 01:04:23.450 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Oh, yeah, yeah.

01:04:23.450 --> 01:04:24.688 align:middle line:90%
They can be complex numbers.

01:04:24.688 --> 01:04:25.730 align:middle line:90%
They can be real numbers.

01:04:25.730 --> 01:04:28.415 align:middle line:84%
It's just-- f0, f1
is just some numbers.

01:04:28.415 --> 01:04:30.920 align:middle line:90%


01:04:30.920 --> 01:04:31.420 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:04:31.420 --> 01:04:33.400 align:middle line:90%
For example-- yeah.

01:04:33.400 --> 01:04:36.715 align:middle line:84%
So suppose f is a
Gaussian function.

01:04:36.715 --> 01:04:41.290 align:middle line:90%


01:04:41.290 --> 01:04:42.370 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:04:42.370 --> 01:04:44.890 align:middle line:90%
And then you just write 1--

01:04:44.890 --> 01:04:46.090 align:middle line:90%
yeah, yeah.

01:04:46.090 --> 01:04:47.260 align:middle line:90%
Say exponential theta.

01:04:47.260 --> 01:04:48.630 align:middle line:90%
1 plus theta.

01:04:48.630 --> 01:04:49.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:04:49.130 --> 01:04:50.710 align:middle line:84%
Is exponential from
just one-- just

01:04:50.710 --> 01:04:52.690 align:middle line:90%
do Taylor expansion of theta.

01:04:52.690 --> 01:04:55.420 align:middle line:84%
And the f0 and 1 just come
from the Taylor expansion

01:04:55.420 --> 01:04:57.760 align:middle line:84%
of whatever function
you're looking at here.

01:04:57.760 --> 01:04:58.540 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:04:58.540 --> 01:05:00.340 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, similarly--
the same thing.

01:05:00.340 --> 01:05:02.000 align:middle line:90%
1 plus theta.

01:05:02.000 --> 01:05:03.890 align:middle line:84%
So you have a
function like that.

01:05:03.890 --> 01:05:06.552 align:middle line:90%
So it's just 1 minus theta.

01:05:06.552 --> 01:05:07.510 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, it's very simple.

01:05:07.510 --> 01:05:09.280 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:05:09.280 --> 01:05:12.650 align:middle line:84%
So the functions of these
variables are very simple.

01:05:12.650 --> 01:05:13.150 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:13.150 --> 01:05:16.940 align:middle line:90%


01:05:16.940 --> 01:05:17.720 align:middle line:90%
Good.

01:05:17.720 --> 01:05:20.330 align:middle line:84%
So we talked about
the functions.

01:05:20.330 --> 01:05:22.890 align:middle line:84%
So we talked about
the functions.

01:05:22.890 --> 01:05:24.720 align:middle line:90%
Also, we talked about the--

01:05:24.720 --> 01:05:26.130 align:middle line:90%
yeah, the functions of them.

01:05:26.130 --> 01:05:27.390 align:middle line:90%
We talked about derivatives.

01:05:27.390 --> 01:05:30.660 align:middle line:84%
And then we need to talk about
the integrals of them, OK--

01:05:30.660 --> 01:05:32.650 align:middle line:90%
so how to define integration.

01:05:32.650 --> 01:05:36.080 align:middle line:90%


01:05:36.080 --> 01:05:39.200 align:middle line:84%
So now let's talk about
how to do integration.

01:05:39.200 --> 01:05:41.540 align:middle line:90%
So how do you do integrals?

01:05:41.540 --> 01:05:44.612 align:middle line:90%
Because we need to do the--

01:05:44.612 --> 01:05:46.070 align:middle line:84%
to be able to do
path integrals, we

01:05:46.070 --> 01:05:48.350 align:middle line:84%
need to integrate
over such objects.

01:05:48.350 --> 01:05:50.280 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:05:50.280 --> 01:05:53.040 align:middle line:84%
So to do integration,
then we have

01:05:53.040 --> 01:05:56.755 align:middle line:84%
to specify the rule
for integration

01:05:56.755 --> 01:05:58.880 align:middle line:84%
because it's no longer
intuitive like a derivative.

01:05:58.880 --> 01:06:00.380 align:middle line:84%
You can just take
the derivative.

01:06:00.380 --> 01:06:01.100 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:06:01.100 --> 01:06:05.270 align:middle line:84%
So integration-- we have
to specify the rule.

01:06:05.270 --> 01:06:09.230 align:middle line:84%
And then the idea is
you use the standard,

01:06:09.230 --> 01:06:12.140 align:middle line:84%
the rule for integration,
and then translate--

01:06:12.140 --> 01:06:13.800 align:middle line:90%
apply to this case.

01:06:13.800 --> 01:06:14.300 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:06:14.300 --> 01:06:20.030 align:middle line:84%
So the rules we are going to
require for the integration

01:06:20.030 --> 01:06:21.219 align:middle line:90%
are the following.

01:06:21.219 --> 01:06:56.190 align:middle line:90%


01:06:56.190 --> 01:07:03.060 align:middle line:84%
So the first rule is that the
integration should be linear.

01:07:03.060 --> 01:07:03.560 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:07:03.560 --> 01:07:07.160 align:middle line:84%
So if I have, say, an
integration of f theta--

01:07:07.160 --> 01:07:13.772 align:middle line:84%
I have two functions, f
theta a plus g theta b.

01:07:13.772 --> 01:07:15.540 align:middle line:90%
And a and b are some numbers.

01:07:15.540 --> 01:07:18.120 align:middle line:84%
They can either be
ordinary C-numbers.

01:07:18.120 --> 01:07:21.770 align:middle line:84%
They also can be Grassmann
numbers, which anti-commute.

01:07:21.770 --> 01:07:23.090 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:07:23.090 --> 01:07:25.140 align:middle line:90%
And then by linear--

01:07:25.140 --> 01:07:29.090 align:middle line:90%


01:07:29.090 --> 01:07:31.070 align:middle line:84%
but the integration
operation is linear.

01:07:31.070 --> 01:07:36.430 align:middle line:84%
This means that this is
the same as the d theta f

01:07:36.430 --> 01:07:42.030 align:middle line:84%
theta times a, where
a just constant

01:07:42.030 --> 01:07:44.730 align:middle line:84%
so you can just take it
outside of the integral.

01:07:44.730 --> 01:07:50.610 align:middle line:90%
d theta, g theta b.

01:07:50.610 --> 01:07:52.000 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:07:52.000 --> 01:07:55.330 align:middle line:84%
So it should be
linear, the operation.

01:07:55.330 --> 01:07:58.120 align:middle line:90%


01:07:58.120 --> 01:08:05.260 align:middle line:84%
And the second rule which we
require for such integration

01:08:05.260 --> 01:08:07.980 align:middle line:84%
is that the total
derivative should be 0.

01:08:07.980 --> 01:08:09.860 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:08:09.860 --> 01:08:20.160 align:middle line:84%
So the total derivative
should be equal to 0.

01:08:20.160 --> 01:08:22.750 align:middle line:90%


01:08:22.750 --> 01:08:24.229 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:08:24.229 --> 01:08:26.359 align:middle line:84%
And turns out that
these two conditions

01:08:26.359 --> 01:08:31.069 align:middle line:84%
can be uniquely then it
is enough to actually fix

01:08:31.069 --> 01:08:36.390 align:middle line:84%
the other properties
of the integral.

01:08:36.390 --> 01:08:36.890 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:08:36.890 --> 01:08:40.569 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, it just can be
used to fix the integral.

01:08:40.569 --> 01:08:41.290 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:08:41.290 --> 01:08:47.750 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] in not
all derivatives [INAUDIBLE]

01:08:47.750 --> 01:08:49.435 align:middle line:90%
when the boundary [INAUDIBLE]?

01:08:49.435 --> 01:08:50.060 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

01:08:50.060 --> 01:08:51.569 align:middle line:90%
Here, we don't have a boundary.

01:08:51.569 --> 01:08:53.430 align:middle line:90%
It's not required to be 0.

01:08:53.430 --> 01:08:55.080 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so theta--
yeah, we don't know

01:08:55.080 --> 01:08:58.090 align:middle line:84%
how to specify the
boundaries for theta.

01:08:58.090 --> 01:08:59.744 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:08:59.744 --> 01:09:05.609 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: How does [INAUDIBLE]
multiply by it [INAUDIBLE]

01:09:05.609 --> 01:09:07.890 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

01:09:07.890 --> 01:09:09.979 align:middle line:90%
You say this one?

01:09:09.979 --> 01:09:13.920 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: No,
[INAUDIBLE] symbol.

01:09:13.920 --> 01:09:15.819 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

