Sorry.

01:09:16.319 --> 01:09:16.950 align:middle line:90%
Say it again?

01:09:16.950 --> 01:09:19.615 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Like,
suppose [INAUDIBLE]

01:09:19.615 --> 01:09:21.240 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: Yeah, yeah,
yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:09:21.240 --> 01:09:23.535 align:middle line:84%
Indeed, it does not
determine-- yeah,

01:09:23.535 --> 01:09:25.359 align:middle line:84%
it only determines
up to a constant.

01:09:25.359 --> 01:09:25.859 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:09:25.859 --> 01:09:28.955 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, but then you
can fix that constant.

01:09:28.955 --> 01:09:30.830 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, I'm going to talk
about it immediately.

01:09:30.830 --> 01:09:31.859 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:09:31.859 --> 01:09:33.380 align:middle line:90%
Good?

01:09:33.380 --> 01:09:36.840 align:middle line:90%
So we have these two conditions.

01:09:36.840 --> 01:09:39.859 align:middle line:84%
So let's see what these
two conditions tell us.

01:09:39.859 --> 01:09:40.700 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:09:40.700 --> 01:09:46.609 align:middle line:84%
So from this condition two,
we conclude that d theta f2

01:09:46.609 --> 01:09:50.880 align:middle line:90%
is equal to 0 because of the--

01:09:50.880 --> 01:09:52.770 align:middle line:90%
the derivative of f theta--

01:09:52.770 --> 01:09:54.805 align:middle line:90%
or sorry, just f1 equal to 0.

01:09:54.805 --> 01:09:55.305 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:09:55.305 --> 01:09:58.050 align:middle line:90%


01:09:58.050 --> 01:10:01.360 align:middle line:84%
We write-- yeah,
just f1 equal to 0.

01:10:01.360 --> 01:10:06.708 align:middle line:84%
And since f1 is a C-number,
we can take this f1 outside

01:10:06.708 --> 01:10:07.375 align:middle line:90%
of the integral.

01:10:07.375 --> 01:10:11.390 align:middle line:90%


01:10:11.390 --> 01:10:13.490 align:middle line:84%
So that means this
is equal to 0.

01:10:13.490 --> 01:10:17.210 align:middle line:84%
So that means that the
theta 1 is equal to 0.

01:10:17.210 --> 01:10:18.260 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:10:18.260 --> 01:10:23.305 align:middle line:84%
So just d theta any
constant, it should be 0.

01:10:23.305 --> 01:10:24.513 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:10:24.513 --> 01:10:25.930 align:middle line:84%
Just any constant,
it should be 0.

01:10:25.930 --> 01:10:28.270 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:10:28.270 --> 01:10:33.785 align:middle line:84%
So this is one condition--
so one thing we deduce.

01:10:33.785 --> 01:10:36.440 align:middle line:90%


01:10:36.440 --> 01:10:38.510 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:10:38.510 --> 01:10:40.550 align:middle line:84%
So now let's call
this property 3 --

01:10:40.550 --> 01:10:44.160 align:middle line:84%
equation three this one
follows from the one and two.

01:10:44.160 --> 01:10:50.032 align:middle line:90%


01:10:50.032 --> 01:10:55.460 align:middle line:84%
So now remember from the
property of f theta equal

01:10:55.460 --> 01:10:57.740 align:middle line:90%
to f0 plus f1 theta--

01:10:57.740 --> 01:11:04.961 align:middle line:84%
so that means d theta f
theta is equal to d theta

01:11:04.961 --> 01:11:07.680 align:middle line:90%
f0 plus f1 theta.

01:11:07.680 --> 01:11:10.450 align:middle line:90%


01:11:10.450 --> 01:11:10.950 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:11:10.950 --> 01:11:14.680 align:middle line:84%
So that means-- so if we
use this property one,

01:11:14.680 --> 01:11:18.280 align:middle line:84%
you can take this
constant outside it.

01:11:18.280 --> 01:11:18.780 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:11:18.780 --> 01:11:21.390 align:middle line:90%
And this term is 0.

01:11:21.390 --> 01:11:24.550 align:middle line:90%
So you just get the second term.

01:11:24.550 --> 01:11:27.670 align:middle line:84%
You just get f1, d
theta and the theta.

01:11:27.670 --> 01:11:31.300 align:middle line:90%


01:11:31.300 --> 01:11:33.800 align:middle line:84%
So now if we just fix
the value of this object,

01:11:33.800 --> 01:11:36.570 align:middle line:90%
then we fix the full integral.

01:11:36.570 --> 01:11:38.370 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:11:38.370 --> 01:11:42.000 align:middle line:84%
And so you just fix
this object to be 1.

01:11:42.000 --> 01:11:43.800 align:middle line:90%
So we just fix--

01:11:43.800 --> 01:11:46.320 align:middle line:90%


01:11:46.320 --> 01:11:48.650 align:middle line:90%
define it to be 1.

01:11:48.650 --> 01:11:49.150 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:11:49.150 --> 01:11:50.640 align:middle line:90%
Define up to a constant.

01:11:50.640 --> 01:11:52.210 align:middle line:90%
We just define it be 1.

01:11:52.210 --> 01:11:52.710 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:52.710 --> 01:11:54.640 align:middle line:90%
So that's it.

01:11:54.640 --> 01:11:57.640 align:middle line:84%
So that is fully
specified to the rule.

01:11:57.640 --> 01:12:07.465 align:middle line:84%
And then we conclude that d
theta f theta is equal to f1.

01:12:07.465 --> 01:12:13.370 align:middle line:90%


01:12:13.370 --> 01:12:15.005 align:middle line:90%
So now you notice--

01:12:15.005 --> 01:12:17.600 align:middle line:90%


01:12:17.600 --> 01:12:20.310 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so this is the
rule you should remember.

01:12:20.310 --> 01:12:24.690 align:middle line:84%
So now you notice that
this is the same as you

01:12:24.690 --> 01:12:26.100 align:middle line:90%
take the derivative of theta.

01:12:26.100 --> 01:12:28.590 align:middle line:90%


01:12:28.590 --> 01:12:29.090 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:12:29.090 --> 01:12:33.780 align:middle line:84%
So this story is a
little bit funny.

01:12:33.780 --> 01:12:34.280 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:12:34.280 --> 01:12:35.870 align:middle line:84%
So the integration
of a function is

01:12:35.870 --> 01:12:38.500 align:middle line:84%
the same as the derivative
of the function.

01:12:38.500 --> 01:12:39.000 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:12:39.000 --> 01:12:41.450 align:middle line:90%


01:12:41.450 --> 01:12:41.950 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:12:41.950 --> 01:12:43.120 align:middle line:90%
That's it.

01:12:43.120 --> 01:12:49.210 align:middle line:84%
So if the calculus for ordinary
variables are such simple of--

01:12:49.210 --> 01:12:53.330 align:middle line:84%
[CHUCKLES]---- when we learn
calculus, it will be much,

01:12:53.330 --> 01:12:55.330 align:middle line:90%
much easier.

01:12:55.330 --> 01:12:55.850 align:middle line:90%
But yeah.

01:12:55.850 --> 01:12:56.350 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:12:56.350 --> 01:12:58.625 align:middle line:84%
So these Grassmann
variables are very simple.

01:12:58.625 --> 01:12:59.125 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:12:59.125 --> 01:13:02.830 align:middle line:90%


01:13:02.830 --> 01:13:05.440 align:middle line:90%
Any questions on this?

01:13:05.440 --> 01:13:06.550 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:13:06.550 --> 01:13:09.878 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So what's the
point in defining integration

01:13:09.878 --> 01:13:11.630 align:middle line:84%
in this way if it
ends up just being

01:13:11.630 --> 01:13:13.702 align:middle line:90%
the same as the derivative one?

01:13:13.702 --> 01:13:17.264 align:middle line:84%
Is it useful to have both
integration and derivatives

01:13:17.264 --> 01:13:20.140 align:middle line:84%
in [INAUDIBLE] if they
did the same thing?

01:13:20.140 --> 01:13:21.970 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

01:13:21.970 --> 01:13:24.490 align:middle line:84%
So this is for the
single variable, right?

01:13:24.490 --> 01:13:26.050 align:middle line:84%
When you go to
the multivariable,

01:13:26.050 --> 01:13:28.430 align:middle line:84%
then things are a little
bit more intricate.

01:13:28.430 --> 01:13:28.930 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:13:28.930 --> 01:13:31.360 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, but this rule will apply.

01:13:31.360 --> 01:13:34.930 align:middle line:84%
This integration
rule is general.

01:13:34.930 --> 01:13:35.946 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:13:35.946 --> 01:13:37.696 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Why dont you
define the integral

01:13:37.696 --> 01:13:41.010 align:middle line:84%
as the opposite of the-- like,
the reverse the derivative?

01:13:41.010 --> 01:13:43.176 align:middle line:84%
Because now, for example,
integrating and taking

01:13:43.176 --> 01:13:46.722 align:middle line:90%
the derivative [INAUDIBLE]

01:13:46.722 --> 01:13:47.680 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: That's right.

01:13:47.680 --> 01:13:50.290 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, just you don't know how
to do that inverse operation

01:13:50.290 --> 01:13:50.948 align:middle line:90%
anymore.

01:13:50.948 --> 01:13:51.490 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: OK.

01:13:51.490 --> 01:13:51.760 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

01:13:51.760 --> 01:13:54.100 align:middle line:84%
Just those kind of objects
are sufficiently weird.

01:13:54.100 --> 01:13:55.630 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, it's not easy.

01:13:55.630 --> 01:13:56.680 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:13:56.680 --> 01:14:00.940 align:middle line:90%
So the basic idea, I think--

01:14:00.940 --> 01:14:04.680 align:middle line:84%
so you say, why Feynman
didn't come up with this?

01:14:04.680 --> 01:14:06.270 align:middle line:84%
Because if you just
say, oh, I have

01:14:06.270 --> 01:14:08.890 align:middle line:84%
to do anti-commuting,
that's not enough.

01:14:08.890 --> 01:14:11.960 align:middle line:84%
You have to invent the
whole calculus for this kind

01:14:11.960 --> 01:14:13.550 align:middle line:90%
of anti-commuting object.

01:14:13.550 --> 01:14:15.470 align:middle line:84%
And now the question
is that, how

01:14:15.470 --> 01:14:17.960 align:middle line:84%
do you invent such a
calculus so that it's

01:14:17.960 --> 01:14:21.800 align:middle line:84%
as natural as possible
compared to the standard way?

01:14:21.800 --> 01:14:22.550 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, yeah.

01:14:22.550 --> 01:14:24.830 align:middle line:84%
And so I think this
is a set of rule

01:14:24.830 --> 01:14:27.440 align:middle line:90%
which seems to work very well.

01:14:27.440 --> 01:14:31.100 align:middle line:90%


01:14:31.100 --> 01:14:32.890 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:14:32.890 --> 01:14:33.830 align:middle line:90%
So yeah.

01:14:33.830 --> 01:14:34.330 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:14:34.330 --> 01:14:36.495 align:middle line:84%
So when we say that
Feynman missed it,

01:14:36.495 --> 01:14:37.870 align:middle line:84%
it's not that he
missed something

01:14:37.870 --> 01:14:39.370 align:middle line:90%
that's just a trivial idea.

01:14:39.370 --> 01:14:41.200 align:middle line:84%
He actually missed
the whole calculus.

01:14:41.200 --> 01:14:41.700 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:14:41.700 --> 01:14:52.198 align:middle line:90%


01:14:52.198 --> 01:14:53.990 align:middle line:84%
So now let's just make
a couple of remarks.

01:14:53.990 --> 01:15:06.950 align:middle line:90%


01:15:06.950 --> 01:15:19.910 align:middle line:84%
So suppose eta is another
Grassmann variable.

01:15:19.910 --> 01:15:20.410 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:15:20.410 --> 01:15:24.196 align:middle line:90%


01:15:24.196 --> 01:15:27.320 align:middle line:84%
It means that it's
also anti-commute.

01:15:27.320 --> 01:15:34.600 align:middle line:84%
So now if we put
eta before f theta--

01:15:34.600 --> 01:15:37.420 align:middle line:90%


01:15:37.420 --> 01:15:39.500 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:15:39.500 --> 01:15:43.930 align:middle line:84%
And now, because eta have
nothing to do with theta,

01:15:43.930 --> 01:15:47.880 align:middle line:84%
you should be able to take
it outside of the integral.

01:15:47.880 --> 01:15:50.310 align:middle line:84%
But different
variables anti-commute.

01:15:50.310 --> 01:15:54.660 align:middle line:84%
So when you take eta
outside the thing,

01:15:54.660 --> 01:15:56.690 align:middle line:84%
the rule is that you
can just take it out.

01:15:56.690 --> 01:15:58.290 align:middle line:84%
It commutes through
this d theta.

01:15:58.290 --> 01:16:00.180 align:middle line:90%
You get a minus sign.

01:16:00.180 --> 01:16:07.200 align:middle line:84%
So you just get the
eta d theta f theta.

01:16:07.200 --> 01:16:07.770 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:16:07.770 --> 01:16:11.601 align:middle line:90%
So this becomes just f1.

01:16:11.601 --> 01:16:13.550 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:16:13.550 --> 01:16:17.990 align:middle line:84%
So you can show that this
rule, which I'm saying here,

01:16:17.990 --> 01:16:21.430 align:middle line:84%
is compatible with
also this rule.

01:16:21.430 --> 01:16:21.930 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:16:21.930 --> 01:16:23.580 align:middle line:84%
It's also compatible
with this rule

01:16:23.580 --> 01:16:26.580 align:middle line:84%
because you can
also commute the eta

01:16:26.580 --> 01:16:29.040 align:middle line:90%
with f inside of the integral.

01:16:29.040 --> 01:16:31.090 align:middle line:90%
And then you can use this rule.

01:16:31.090 --> 01:16:33.090 align:middle line:84%
And you can show these
two rules are compatible.

01:16:33.090 --> 01:16:33.590 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:16:33.590 --> 01:16:36.230 align:middle line:90%


01:16:36.230 --> 01:16:37.475 align:middle line:90%
So this is the first remark.

01:16:37.475 --> 01:16:47.030 align:middle line:90%


01:16:47.030 --> 01:16:49.160 align:middle line:90%
The second remark is that the--

01:16:49.160 --> 01:16:50.900 align:middle line:84%
it's hard to do
integration by parts.

01:16:50.900 --> 01:16:55.100 align:middle line:90%


01:16:55.100 --> 01:17:01.320 align:middle line:84%
So now let's-- consider
integral like this.

01:17:01.320 --> 01:17:03.520 align:middle line:90%
a would be some ordinary--

01:17:03.520 --> 01:17:04.755 align:middle line:90%
a is just some number.

01:17:04.755 --> 01:17:07.330 align:middle line:90%


01:17:07.330 --> 01:17:09.580 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:17:09.580 --> 01:17:14.380 align:middle line:84%
So you can just
expand this trivially.

01:17:14.380 --> 01:17:19.470 align:middle line:84%
So this just gives-- you
just find this f1 times a.

01:17:19.470 --> 01:17:20.190 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:17:20.190 --> 01:17:22.080 align:middle line:90%
Just f1 times a.

01:17:22.080 --> 01:17:23.970 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:17:23.970 --> 01:17:27.360 align:middle line:84%
And of course, f1
times a is also

01:17:27.360 --> 01:17:35.780 align:middle line:84%
the same as a times d
theta prime f theta prime.

01:17:35.780 --> 01:17:40.250 align:middle line:84%
If theta prime is a theta
because it's a dummy variable.

01:17:40.250 --> 01:17:41.000 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't matter.

01:17:41.000 --> 01:17:41.500 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:17:41.500 --> 01:17:44.080 align:middle line:90%


01:17:44.080 --> 01:17:46.960 align:middle line:90%
So this tells you--

01:17:46.960 --> 01:17:49.570 align:middle line:90%


01:17:49.570 --> 01:17:51.580 align:middle line:84%
so then when
comparing these two--

01:17:51.580 --> 01:17:54.020 align:middle line:90%


01:17:54.020 --> 01:17:54.520 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:17:54.520 --> 01:17:58.040 align:middle line:84%
So this is like a
change of variable.

01:17:58.040 --> 01:17:58.880 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:17:58.880 --> 01:17:59.600 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:17:59.600 --> 01:18:03.056 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So if eta has to obey
anti-commutation with d theta,

01:18:03.056 --> 01:18:05.476 align:middle line:84%
why doesn't theta have to
obey anti-commutation with

01:18:05.476 --> 01:18:06.450 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE]?

01:18:06.450 --> 01:18:07.440 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: Yeah.

01:18:07.440 --> 01:18:08.440 align:middle line:90%
Theta does have two.

01:18:08.440 --> 01:18:08.940 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:18:08.940 --> 01:18:10.804 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: But then
why [INAUDIBLE]??

01:18:10.804 --> 01:18:14.680 align:middle line:90%


01:18:14.680 --> 01:18:16.550 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: OK.

01:18:16.550 --> 01:18:20.980 align:middle line:84%
But d theta and theta are
two different objects, right?

01:18:20.980 --> 01:18:22.840 align:middle line:84%
They anti-commute
against each other.

01:18:22.840 --> 01:18:26.650 align:middle line:84%
But this theta means the
infinitesimal variation

01:18:26.650 --> 01:18:31.020 align:middle line:84%
of theta, of course, even though
we cannot quantify what this

01:18:31.020 --> 01:18:33.420 align:middle line:90%
infinitesimal variation means.

01:18:33.420 --> 01:18:35.650 align:middle line:84%
But these two are
different object.

01:18:35.650 --> 01:18:36.150 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:18:36.150 --> 01:18:37.442 align:middle line:90%
So their product is not-- yeah.

01:18:37.442 --> 01:18:39.870 align:middle line:90%


01:18:39.870 --> 01:18:40.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:18:40.640 --> 01:18:41.140 align:middle line:90%
Good.

01:18:41.140 --> 01:18:43.190 align:middle line:90%
So this tells you--

01:18:43.190 --> 01:18:46.760 align:middle line:84%
so normally when we do
a change of variable--

01:18:46.760 --> 01:18:49.590 align:middle line:90%


01:18:49.590 --> 01:18:53.930 align:middle line:84%
so this means that when you
do the change of variable,

01:18:53.930 --> 01:18:57.640 align:middle line:90%
theta prime is equal to a theta.

01:18:57.640 --> 01:19:02.110 align:middle line:84%
And d theta prime is actually
equal to 1 over a d theta,

01:19:02.110 --> 01:19:04.600 align:middle line:90%
OK, if you compare these two.

01:19:04.600 --> 01:19:06.160 align:middle line:90%
So now this is a very--

01:19:06.160 --> 01:19:08.950 align:middle line:84%
so now, again, this is
opposite to the standard story.

01:19:08.950 --> 01:19:10.000 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:19:10.000 --> 01:19:14.950 align:middle line:84%
So d theta prime is actually
equal to 1 over a d theta.

01:19:14.950 --> 01:19:15.450 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:19:15.450 --> 01:19:18.340 align:middle line:90%


01:19:18.340 --> 01:19:18.840 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:19:18.840 --> 01:19:22.530 align:middle line:90%
So let's conclude here.

01:19:22.530 --> 01:19:26.330 align:middle line:90%


01:19:26.330 --> 01:19:26.830 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

